WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.320 --> 00:00:05.290
BORIS: Today with
us is Roberto Trotta

00:00:05.290 --> 00:00:08.590
with his book, "The
Edge of the Sky."

00:00:08.590 --> 00:00:11.970
It's going to be an interesting
cosmology talk for those of you

00:00:11.970 --> 00:00:15.890
who would like to learn
more about cosmology

00:00:15.890 --> 00:00:17.740
but in simple words.

00:00:17.740 --> 00:00:20.020
So let me just give you
a brief introduction.

00:00:20.020 --> 00:00:22.520
Roberto Trotta is a
theoretical cosmologist

00:00:22.520 --> 00:00:26.550
in the astrophysics group of
the Imperial College in London.

00:00:26.550 --> 00:00:29.720
He has held research positions
at the University of Geneva

00:00:29.720 --> 00:00:33.480
and the University of Oxford,
as well as visiting positions

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:36.637
at the African Institute for
Mathematical Sciences in Cape

00:00:36.637 --> 00:00:42.240
Town, the Institut Astrophysique
de Paris, and the University

00:00:42.240 --> 00:00:44.750
of California at Santa Barbara.

00:00:44.750 --> 00:00:48.230
One of the world's leading
figures in astrostatistics,

00:00:48.230 --> 00:00:52.140
and new discipline focusing on
the use of statistical methods

00:00:52.140 --> 00:00:55.470
to solve problems in
cosmology and astrophysics,

00:00:55.470 --> 00:00:57.960
he has published more
than 50 scientific papers,

00:00:57.960 --> 00:01:00.950
contributed to two books,
and received numerous awards

00:01:00.950 --> 00:01:04.970
for his research, including the
Michelson Prize of Case Western

00:01:04.970 --> 00:01:08.650
Reserve University, the Lord
Kelvin Award of the British

00:01:08.650 --> 00:01:11.500
Association for the
Advancement of Science,

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:14.620
and a public engagement
fellowship by the Science

00:01:14.620 --> 00:01:17.650
and Technology Facilities
Council in the UK.

00:01:17.650 --> 00:01:20.940
Please join me in welcoming
Roberto to Google.

00:01:24.635 --> 00:01:26.010
ROBERTO TROTTA:
Thank you, Boris.

00:01:26.010 --> 00:01:27.280
And good afternoon, everyone.

00:01:27.280 --> 00:01:29.830
And thanks for being here today.

00:01:29.830 --> 00:01:31.510
I'm very pleased
to be here today

00:01:31.510 --> 00:01:35.590
in such an amazing place
full of computer people who

00:01:35.590 --> 00:01:38.350
can search the entire worldwide
computer to answer all

00:01:38.350 --> 00:01:42.320
of your questions and can draw
a picture of the streets in

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:42.820
[INAUDIBLE].

00:01:44.150 --> 00:01:46.370
And now, so I hear,
you're even building

00:01:46.370 --> 00:01:48.440
cars that can drive alone.

00:01:48.440 --> 00:01:50.190
So this is really the
perfect place for me

00:01:50.190 --> 00:01:53.400
to talk about my new book,
"The Edge of the Sky."

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:57.074
This book came out of a
straightforward simple idea,

00:01:57.074 --> 00:01:58.490
that it should be
possible to talk

00:01:58.490 --> 00:02:01.650
about very hard things
in a straightforward way

00:02:01.650 --> 00:02:03.210
that all people can understand.

00:02:04.272 --> 00:02:06.480
The problem with student
people like myself, you see,

00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:09.060
is that sometimes we get
carried away and speak

00:02:09.060 --> 00:02:11.660
about our work using
words in a tone

00:02:11.660 --> 00:02:13.590
that only other student
people can understand.

00:02:14.930 --> 00:02:16.730
This makes it not
possible to have

00:02:16.730 --> 00:02:19.970
a conversation with other
people, people like you.

00:02:19.970 --> 00:02:22.250
After a little
while, your eyes will

00:02:22.250 --> 00:02:25.300
begin to stare into empty
space, and you'll probably

00:02:25.300 --> 00:02:28.129
walk away as soon as you
can with a silent sigh,

00:02:28.129 --> 00:02:29.045
happy to have escaped.

00:02:30.590 --> 00:02:34.220
A way to avoid all that is by
talking with only the most used

00:02:34.220 --> 00:02:36.910
ten hundred words
in this tongue.

00:02:36.910 --> 00:02:38.350
When I heard about
this, I thought

00:02:38.350 --> 00:02:41.884
it could be fun to use it
to explain the [INAUDIBLE].

00:02:41.884 --> 00:02:43.300
And this is what
my book is about,

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:46.082
and what this here is about.

00:02:46.082 --> 00:02:47.540
I would like to
share with you some

00:02:47.540 --> 00:02:50.340
of the ideas behind the
book and the story of how

00:02:50.340 --> 00:02:53.710
this slightly crazy
idea became reality.

00:02:53.710 --> 00:02:56.870
So you might have thought that
this was a little strange,

00:02:56.870 --> 00:02:57.370
perhaps.

00:02:57.370 --> 00:02:59.840
And you might have thought,
well this is down to the fact

00:02:59.840 --> 00:03:02.820
that I spent way too
much time in Britain.

00:03:02.820 --> 00:03:07.090
And so of course we know that
the United States and Britain

00:03:07.090 --> 00:03:10.330
are two nations which are
separated by the same language.

00:03:10.330 --> 00:03:11.880
But actually, that's
not the reason

00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:13.550
why this sounded a
little bit weird.

00:03:13.550 --> 00:03:15.030
The reason why
this was different

00:03:15.030 --> 00:03:17.980
is because it was written
using only the most common ten

00:03:17.980 --> 00:03:19.780
hundred words in
English, which is

00:03:19.780 --> 00:03:22.077
the idea behind "The
Edge of the Sky."

00:03:22.077 --> 00:03:23.910
As so I just wanted to
give you a little bit

00:03:23.910 --> 00:03:25.940
of a sense for what
this language is about,

00:03:25.940 --> 00:03:27.810
and how it actually
can change the way

00:03:27.810 --> 00:03:29.960
we communicate with each other.

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:33.110
So before I go on,
I'd like to ask

00:03:33.110 --> 00:03:35.485
you to keep your phones on in
case you have switched them

00:03:35.485 --> 00:03:37.609
off-- I hope not-- and
please join the conversation

00:03:37.609 --> 00:03:41.690
on Twitter by getting in touch
with me with my Twitter handle

00:03:41.690 --> 00:03:43.940
and #theedgeofthesky hashtag.

00:03:43.940 --> 00:03:47.430
So let me take a
step back and go back

00:03:47.430 --> 00:03:52.520
to the '60s, at a time
when very little was known

00:03:52.520 --> 00:03:55.000
about the universe
and we didn't have

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:57.600
all of the great data and
the great capabilities

00:03:57.600 --> 00:04:01.450
to observe the sky and the
universe as we do today.

00:04:01.450 --> 00:04:05.400
These two gentlemen came up
with a wonderful discovery

00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:08.090
in 1965, Penzias and Wilson.

00:04:08.090 --> 00:04:12.330
They were working at
Bell Labs in New Jersey,

00:04:12.330 --> 00:04:14.260
not far away from
Princeton in fact.

00:04:14.260 --> 00:04:15.840
And they had a big
microwave antenna

00:04:15.840 --> 00:04:20.040
with which they were looking
into doing some experiments

00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:22.030
in microwave
communication, early days

00:04:22.030 --> 00:04:23.571
still before satellite
communication.

00:04:23.571 --> 00:04:26.930
They were trying to bounce off
the microwaves of some passing

00:04:26.930 --> 00:04:30.240
satellites, trying to
communicate long distance using

00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:30.740
microwaves.

00:04:32.190 --> 00:04:34.870
But the problem was that they
couldn't make their antenna

00:04:34.870 --> 00:04:39.037
work because they kept picking
up a very strange background

00:04:39.037 --> 00:04:41.620
noise, a noise that they didn't
know where it was coming from.

00:04:41.620 --> 00:04:43.970
And they tried very, very
hard to get rid of the noise

00:04:43.970 --> 00:04:45.360
and they couldn't.

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:49.890
At some point then they got in
touch with a team of scientists

00:04:49.890 --> 00:04:52.820
at Princeton who were actually
trying to build an antenna

00:04:52.820 --> 00:04:54.810
to look for this kind of noise.

00:04:54.810 --> 00:04:57.800
And this microwave noise,
this microwave light

00:04:57.800 --> 00:05:02.230
was none other than the light
echo from the Big Bang itself.

00:05:02.230 --> 00:05:05.524
Unbeknownst to them, they'd
discover the [INAUDIBLE]

00:05:05.524 --> 00:05:06.690
radiation from the Big Bang.

00:05:06.690 --> 00:05:08.910
And so in 1965 they
came out with this paper

00:05:08.910 --> 00:05:12.900
here, a paper that in
only one and a half pages

00:05:12.900 --> 00:05:15.080
talks about this
momentous discovery.

00:05:15.080 --> 00:05:17.390
And the title of the
paper is "The Measurement

00:05:17.390 --> 00:05:22.022
of Excess Antenna
Temperature at 4080 Mc/s".

00:05:22.022 --> 00:05:24.990
And that's not a great
title, to be fair.

00:05:24.990 --> 00:05:28.644
What they were trying to say
is, we have found evidence

00:05:28.644 --> 00:05:30.060
that the universe
had a beginning.

00:05:30.060 --> 00:05:33.170
We've discover the luminous
echo from the Big Bang.

00:05:33.170 --> 00:05:35.530
But this title is kind
of jargony and not really

00:05:35.530 --> 00:05:38.902
accessible to anybody,
even them to be fair.

00:05:38.902 --> 00:05:40.860
They didn't actually know
what they discovered.

00:05:40.860 --> 00:05:42.787
It was the Princeton
team that told them

00:05:42.787 --> 00:05:44.670
what the discovery mean

00:05:44.670 --> 00:05:47.130
And sometimes in
communicating the science,

00:05:47.130 --> 00:05:49.070
scientific papers are
perhaps not the best way

00:05:49.070 --> 00:05:51.050
of getting the message across.

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:55.140
So you might think 1965
was early days still

00:05:55.140 --> 00:05:56.460
in science and astrophysics.

00:05:56.460 --> 00:05:57.960
And certainly,
science communication

00:05:57.960 --> 00:06:00.390
wasn't as developed
as it is today.

00:06:00.390 --> 00:06:02.695
And so things must have
improved in the meantime.

00:06:02.695 --> 00:06:05.550
So let's have a look at another
momentous discovery in my field

00:06:05.550 --> 00:06:07.690
in astrophysics,
a discovery that

00:06:07.690 --> 00:06:11.110
was worthy of a Nobel
Prize for physics in 2011.

00:06:11.110 --> 00:06:15.220
And here is a paper in 1999,
published in the "Astrophysical

00:06:15.220 --> 00:06:18.770
Journal" with a title that
goes as follows, "Measurements

00:06:18.770 --> 00:06:22.420
of Omega and Lambda from 42
High-Redshift Supernovae".

00:06:22.420 --> 00:06:25.450
Now, wherever you see Greek
letters in scientific papers,

00:06:25.450 --> 00:06:27.630
and specifically
astrophysical papers,

00:06:27.630 --> 00:06:29.390
that's a sign that
we the scientists are

00:06:29.390 --> 00:06:31.765
trying to be clever and smart,
and trying to make it look

00:06:31.765 --> 00:06:34.098
like as if we know a lot about
what we're talking about,

00:06:34.098 --> 00:06:35.420
but we don't necessarily.

00:06:35.420 --> 00:06:36.920
And so the paper
goes on [INAUDIBLE]

00:06:36.920 --> 00:06:39.737
"we report measurement of
the mass density [INAUDIBLE]

00:06:39.737 --> 00:06:41.820
and cosmological constant
density omega and lambda

00:06:41.820 --> 00:06:44.010
of the universe,
based on the analysis

00:06:44.010 --> 00:06:46.480
of 42 type 1a supernovae
discovered by the supernova

00:06:46.480 --> 00:06:48.609
[INAUDIBLE] project,
et cetera, et cetera.

00:06:48.609 --> 00:06:49.900
And it goes on, and on, and on.

00:06:49.900 --> 00:06:52.500
And so what they're trying
to say with this paper is,

00:06:52.500 --> 00:06:54.400
we've discovered evidence
that the universe

00:06:54.400 --> 00:06:56.410
is expanding in
an accelerated way

00:06:56.410 --> 00:06:58.690
and is being ripped
apart by an unknown force

00:06:58.690 --> 00:07:00.620
that we call dark energy.

00:07:00.620 --> 00:07:02.180
And none of that
really comes through

00:07:02.180 --> 00:07:05.632
if you read the paper, or the
abstract, or indeed the title.

00:07:05.632 --> 00:07:06.340
So that was 1999.

00:07:06.340 --> 00:07:08.840
You might think, well
actually nowadays,

00:07:08.840 --> 00:07:11.400
21st century with
all the social media

00:07:11.400 --> 00:07:15.000
and so on, communicating
exciting science

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:17.260
must have become so much easier.

00:07:17.260 --> 00:07:19.400
So let's have a look
at another discovery,

00:07:19.400 --> 00:07:22.780
another Nobel Prize for physics,
this time at the large hadron

00:07:22.780 --> 00:07:25.590
colider, the particle
accelerator at CERN in Geneva.

00:07:25.590 --> 00:07:27.680
And here the title
is, "Observation

00:07:27.680 --> 00:07:31.350
of a new Boson on a Mass of
125 GeV with the CMS Experiment

00:07:31.350 --> 00:07:32.840
at the LHC".

00:07:32.840 --> 00:07:35.490
Now you can see now that there's
no longer a list of authors.

00:07:35.490 --> 00:07:39.770
There's only a CMS collaboration
tag as a list of authors.

00:07:39.770 --> 00:07:41.550
That's because
science has become

00:07:41.550 --> 00:07:43.460
so big in the
meantime, two people

00:07:43.460 --> 00:07:45.880
from Nobel Prize
for physics in 1965

00:07:45.880 --> 00:07:47.870
the discoverers of the
microwave background,

00:07:47.870 --> 00:07:50.260
about 25 or 30 people
on the previous paper

00:07:50.260 --> 00:07:53.160
for the supernova type
1a dark energy discovery.

00:07:53.160 --> 00:07:56.670
And now the CMS collaboration,
about 5,000 scientists

00:07:56.670 --> 00:07:58.180
working on these big projects.

00:07:58.180 --> 00:07:59.985
So that's how big
science is nowadays.

00:08:01.277 --> 00:08:02.860
And how do they
present these results?

00:08:02.860 --> 00:08:06.160
Well, they say results are
presented-- no we go over

00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:09.750
to passive form to make it
look a bit more impersonal

00:08:09.750 --> 00:08:10.482
and objective.

00:08:10.482 --> 00:08:12.940
"Results are presented from
searches for the standard model

00:08:12.940 --> 00:08:15.570
Higgs boson proton-proton
collisions at square root of s

00:08:15.570 --> 00:08:19.300
equals 7 and 8 TeV in the
Compact Muon Solenoid".

00:08:19.300 --> 00:08:23.240
A compact muon solenoid
is-- [INAUDIBLE]

00:08:23.240 --> 00:08:25.310
is like a five
story high building

00:08:25.310 --> 00:08:29.960
full of instrumented iron and
other computerized detectors.

00:08:29.960 --> 00:08:32.407
That's what "compact"
means nowadays in physics.

00:08:32.407 --> 00:08:34.240
And so the compact muon
solenoid [INAUDIBLE]

00:08:34.240 --> 00:08:35.909
MHC using data
samples corresponding

00:08:35.909 --> 00:08:38.750
to [INAUDIBLE] of up to
5.1 inverse [INAUDIBLE]

00:08:38.750 --> 00:08:42.520
at 7 [INAUDIBLE] and 5.3 inverse
[INAUDIBLE] at 8 [INAUDIBLE]

00:08:42.520 --> 00:08:43.929
et cetera, et cetera.

00:08:43.929 --> 00:08:45.467
And so what are
they trying to say?

00:08:45.467 --> 00:08:47.050
They're trying to
tell us that they've

00:08:47.050 --> 00:08:49.660
discovered the God
particle, the Higgs boson,

00:08:49.660 --> 00:08:52.560
the particle that gives
mass to all other particles.

00:08:52.560 --> 00:08:56.060
And so you can see that
scientific research papers are

00:08:56.060 --> 00:08:59.470
not perhaps the very best places
to look for the excitement

00:08:59.470 --> 00:09:02.020
that all of this
great science actually

00:09:02.020 --> 00:09:03.990
is about and the
great discoveries

00:09:03.990 --> 00:09:06.670
that this science is supposed to
be communicating to the public

00:09:06.670 --> 00:09:07.530
as well.

00:09:07.530 --> 00:09:09.930
And fair enough, those
are scientific papers

00:09:09.930 --> 00:09:11.930
which are written for
specialists by specialists

00:09:11.930 --> 00:09:13.940
and are targeting a very
restricted audience.

00:09:13.940 --> 00:09:16.220
But as a scientist
working in this field,

00:09:16.220 --> 00:09:18.880
my quest has been
for many years now

00:09:18.880 --> 00:09:22.020
to find ways of talking about
these very exciting science

00:09:22.020 --> 00:09:25.890
topics in more accessible,
direct, and exciting ways

00:09:25.890 --> 00:09:28.980
to communicate with the
public and the educated public

00:09:28.980 --> 00:09:31.990
and people who are interested
in these discoveries in a more

00:09:31.990 --> 00:09:32.770
effective way.

00:09:32.770 --> 00:09:35.715
And try to find ways of not
only talking about the science

00:09:35.715 --> 00:09:39.310
that those great discoveries
are about, but also

00:09:39.310 --> 00:09:41.430
about having a
dialogue with people,

00:09:41.430 --> 00:09:43.400
breaking down the
communication barriers,

00:09:43.400 --> 00:09:47.350
the jargon such as those
examples that we just saw

00:09:47.350 --> 00:09:52.090
is raising in our
discussion between ourselves

00:09:52.090 --> 00:09:54.760
and the public, the
scientists and the public.

00:09:54.760 --> 00:09:57.410
So my work in
astrophysics and cosmology

00:09:57.410 --> 00:10:01.565
is about using big data
and astrostatistical--

00:10:01.565 --> 00:10:03.589
that is to say advanced
statistical methods--

00:10:03.589 --> 00:10:05.880
to analyze those big data
and trying to understand them

00:10:05.880 --> 00:10:08.420
in terms of what they mean
for the fundamental nature

00:10:08.420 --> 00:10:10.410
and fundamental theories
of our universe.

00:10:10.410 --> 00:10:13.350
So big questions, such as what
is the nature of dark energy,

00:10:13.350 --> 00:10:15.850
dark matter, stuff that we don't
know in the universe that's

00:10:15.850 --> 00:10:19.270
dark and invisible, and
yet is responsible for 95%

00:10:19.270 --> 00:10:20.250
of the universe?

00:10:20.250 --> 00:10:21.720
What does the
universe come from?

00:10:21.720 --> 00:10:24.090
What will be its final fate?

00:10:24.090 --> 00:10:26.130
So all of those
questions are usually

00:10:26.130 --> 00:10:30.000
exciting to us the scientists,
but also the public at large.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:31.940
How do we talk about
those discoveries

00:10:31.940 --> 00:10:36.110
in a way that's more meaningful
and more interactive, and not

00:10:36.110 --> 00:10:37.877
full of jargon?

00:10:37.877 --> 00:10:39.460
So for a decade now,
I've been looking

00:10:39.460 --> 00:10:41.750
for different ways
of communicating

00:10:41.750 --> 00:10:43.410
this exciting science
with the public.

00:10:43.410 --> 00:10:45.190
And I've tried different things.

00:10:45.190 --> 00:10:48.640
I've tried using food
to talk about cosmology.

00:10:48.640 --> 00:10:50.840
So explaining the
Hubble expansion,

00:10:50.840 --> 00:10:54.640
the expansion of the
universe in terms of pizza

00:10:54.640 --> 00:10:55.570
dough, for example.

00:10:55.570 --> 00:10:58.880
Here you see an
example of our galaxy,

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:02.100
the Milky Way, here, and a model
of the universe expanding here

00:11:02.100 --> 00:11:04.750
with other galaxies-- the other
bits of olives expanding out

00:11:04.750 --> 00:11:05.660
as time goes on.

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:08.380
In this sense, you can
see the universe expands

00:11:08.380 --> 00:11:10.725
and all galaxies move away
from every other galaxy.

00:11:10.725 --> 00:11:14.550
That's a perfect 2-D model
of the universe which

00:11:14.550 --> 00:11:15.925
you can make in
your own kitchen.

00:11:15.925 --> 00:11:16.966
And it works fairly well.

00:11:16.966 --> 00:11:18.745
You can see this
little yardstick, which

00:11:18.745 --> 00:11:21.030
is made of a piece
of bean, I think.

00:11:21.030 --> 00:11:22.835
And you can see
that distances grow.

00:11:22.835 --> 00:11:27.123
And between galaxies here,
it's one bean unit, one

00:11:27.123 --> 00:11:28.860
and a half, two bean units.

00:11:28.860 --> 00:11:30.260
It works.

00:11:30.260 --> 00:11:32.810
So that's a funny
way of engaging

00:11:32.810 --> 00:11:34.510
with the public,
because it's hands on.

00:11:34.510 --> 00:11:36.468
It's stuff that you can
do in your own kitchen.

00:11:36.468 --> 00:11:38.120
And I've taken it
to the next stage,

00:11:38.120 --> 00:11:41.640
and I've tried putting
on a cosmic cookery show.

00:11:41.640 --> 00:11:45.410
And I'm cooking pancakes
with a live audience,

00:11:45.410 --> 00:11:49.350
and because this is in the
UK where health and safety

00:11:49.350 --> 00:11:53.590
laws are very strict, you can
see I even have a little fire

00:11:53.590 --> 00:11:56.110
extinguisher at hand just
in case things go wrong,

00:11:56.110 --> 00:11:59.020
as they do when you
experiment with a microwave

00:11:59.020 --> 00:12:00.660
and then burn chocolate
in a microwave.

00:12:00.660 --> 00:12:02.035
There's lots of
smoke coming out.

00:12:02.035 --> 00:12:03.930
It's very spectacular,
and it's fun.

00:12:03.930 --> 00:12:06.330
It's a way of engaging
the public, as well,

00:12:06.330 --> 00:12:08.650
in a way that's a
little bit different.

00:12:08.650 --> 00:12:10.790
I work with artists
and designers

00:12:10.790 --> 00:12:16.000
to build the artwork that is
inspired by cosmological ideas.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.980
Here is, for
example, a structure,

00:12:18.980 --> 00:12:22.470
a creation that
conceptualizes redshift

00:12:22.470 --> 00:12:24.400
in a slightly different way.

00:12:24.400 --> 00:12:26.150
And I've worked with
architects and others

00:12:26.150 --> 00:12:28.740
to create things like
this pinball machine that

00:12:28.740 --> 00:12:31.570
was exhibited at the
[INAUDIBLE] a few years ago

00:12:31.570 --> 00:12:35.380
that represented some sort
of potential energy idea.

00:12:35.380 --> 00:12:36.879
It would be a long
story, probably

00:12:36.879 --> 00:12:37.920
a story for another talk.

00:12:37.920 --> 00:12:40.045
But the point is that I've
tried different avenues.

00:12:40.045 --> 00:12:42.020
But I was looking
always for something

00:12:42.020 --> 00:12:43.390
that was a little different.

00:12:43.390 --> 00:12:47.750
I was looking for something that
was more immediate and creative

00:12:47.750 --> 00:12:50.660
in a way that would
involve language as well.

00:12:50.660 --> 00:12:52.960
And perhaps all along I
had in the back of my mind

00:12:52.960 --> 00:12:56.830
this great example that goes
back to Ernest Hemingway

00:12:56.830 --> 00:12:57.540
apparently.

00:12:57.540 --> 00:12:59.165
I don't know whether
the story is true,

00:12:59.165 --> 00:13:00.600
but it's attributed to him.

00:13:00.600 --> 00:13:02.990
And the story is that
Hemingway was one day sitting

00:13:02.990 --> 00:13:04.510
around the table
with some friends.

00:13:04.510 --> 00:13:09.160
And those friends challenged
him to construct a novel

00:13:09.160 --> 00:13:12.720
in a very short number
of words, just six works.

00:13:12.720 --> 00:13:14.670
And he said, yes of
course, I can do it.

00:13:14.670 --> 00:13:18.410
And a bet was made, and
he accepted the bet.

00:13:18.410 --> 00:13:21.000
And then he sat there for a few
minutes and thought about it.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:25.170
And he came up with
what has become

00:13:25.170 --> 00:13:29.230
known as a form
of flash fiction.

00:13:29.230 --> 00:13:32.900
And the novel that he wrote
in only six words is this.

00:13:35.450 --> 00:13:40.310
"For sale: baby
shoes, never worn."

00:13:40.310 --> 00:13:41.330
That's quite intense.

00:13:41.330 --> 00:13:44.100
Six words only, there's
and entire world

00:13:44.100 --> 00:13:45.510
behind these six words.

00:13:45.510 --> 00:13:47.600
And there's lots
that remains unsaid,

00:13:47.600 --> 00:13:51.040
but there's lots that stimulates
perhaps your imagination.

00:13:51.040 --> 00:13:52.470
There's more to just the words.

00:13:52.470 --> 00:13:56.650
There's another layer, and
you or us as the readers

00:13:56.650 --> 00:14:02.215
are stimulated to think, what
else is the story going on

00:14:02.215 --> 00:14:04.225
beyond those words and
behind those words?

00:14:04.225 --> 00:14:06.100
And so I was looking
for something like that.

00:14:06.100 --> 00:14:08.630
Some way of
condensing all we know

00:14:08.630 --> 00:14:11.020
about the universe,
all there is,

00:14:11.020 --> 00:14:14.150
in a simple yet imaginative
and creative way.

00:14:15.500 --> 00:14:18.990
Now of course in physics, if you
think about physics and science

00:14:18.990 --> 00:14:21.680
in general, we have
ways of condensing

00:14:21.680 --> 00:14:25.420
a variety of phenomena
down in very simple terms.

00:14:25.420 --> 00:14:27.740
So for example, if we
think about electricity

00:14:27.740 --> 00:14:30.380
and magnetism,
those are phenomena

00:14:30.380 --> 00:14:33.260
that are ubiquitous
in our everyday lives,

00:14:33.260 --> 00:14:37.170
from power generation to all
sorts of electrical tools

00:14:37.170 --> 00:14:39.650
in our households, to
electricity, and lights,

00:14:39.650 --> 00:14:45.660
and telecommunication, and power
again, turbine generation here.

00:14:45.660 --> 00:14:49.660
All of those things are aspects
of the electrical and magnetic

00:14:49.660 --> 00:14:52.180
phenomena that very
much rule our lives,

00:14:52.180 --> 00:14:54.710
or certainly have a
big part in our lives.

00:14:54.710 --> 00:14:58.910
And yet all of this
variety of phenomena

00:14:58.910 --> 00:15:04.150
are down to one single force,
the electromagnetic force which

00:15:04.150 --> 00:15:08.630
can be described in physics
using a very condensed and very

00:15:08.630 --> 00:15:10.630
simple, in a sense, expression.

00:15:10.630 --> 00:15:15.660
A mathematical description which
boils down to this one equation

00:15:15.660 --> 00:15:16.980
here.

00:15:16.980 --> 00:15:20.100
Now I won't unpack this one
equation for you necessarily,

00:15:20.100 --> 00:15:24.710
but I just want to highlight
how physics in general

00:15:24.710 --> 00:15:27.880
is a quest for simplicity,
a quest for beauty,

00:15:27.880 --> 00:15:29.020
a quest for symmetry.

00:15:29.020 --> 00:15:32.770
Although things are
condensed into equations

00:15:32.770 --> 00:15:35.920
such as this one, which is a
compact form of writing down

00:15:35.920 --> 00:15:38.990
the four Maxwell equations
that-- as you might remember

00:15:38.990 --> 00:15:43.640
from high school or university
if you encountered those

00:15:43.640 --> 00:15:45.480
before-- the four
Maxwell's equations

00:15:45.480 --> 00:15:48.060
describe all of the
electromagnetical phenomena

00:15:48.060 --> 00:15:49.060
that we know about.

00:15:49.060 --> 00:15:51.250
And they can all be written
down in one simple line,

00:15:51.250 --> 00:15:53.582
in one single equation,
this equation here.

00:15:53.582 --> 00:15:55.790
But the probem, of course
it that with this language,

00:15:55.790 --> 00:15:58.160
it takes-- in this
form, it will take

00:15:58.160 --> 00:16:00.360
probably a major in
physics understand

00:16:00.360 --> 00:16:01.950
what this form means.

00:16:01.950 --> 00:16:05.370
It is not a way of
presenting electromagnets

00:16:05.370 --> 00:16:07.800
that we're using for our
undergrad physics students.

00:16:07.800 --> 00:16:11.580
And so while there is beauty,
simplicity, symmetry, elegance

00:16:11.580 --> 00:16:14.420
even in equations such as
this, this is not something

00:16:14.420 --> 00:16:16.690
that we can use to
communicate with the public,

00:16:16.690 --> 00:16:18.410
because of this
not only language

00:16:18.410 --> 00:16:20.370
barrier but also
technical knowledge gap.

00:16:20.370 --> 00:16:22.490
So we need to go
beyond this and find

00:16:22.490 --> 00:16:26.280
ways of unpacking the beauty
and elegance of equations

00:16:26.280 --> 00:16:29.780
such as this in a way
that's more immediate, more

00:16:29.780 --> 00:16:31.090
understandable.

00:16:31.090 --> 00:16:33.390
Here is another
example, the universe

00:16:33.390 --> 00:16:37.800
with all its plethora of
phenomena from galaxies

00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:41.260
such as the Andromeda
galaxy-- our neighbor galaxy--

00:16:41.260 --> 00:16:46.050
or binary stars that
eat up each other

00:16:46.050 --> 00:16:47.890
and then explode
in a big explosion

00:16:47.890 --> 00:16:50.740
at the end of their life, to
the distribution of clusters

00:16:50.740 --> 00:16:53.730
in the sky and the dark
matter structures perhaps

00:16:53.730 --> 00:16:54.930
as well in the universe.

00:16:54.930 --> 00:16:58.160
All of this is largely
governed by gravity.

00:16:58.160 --> 00:17:01.509
And gravity, as
Einstein told us in 1915

00:17:01.509 --> 00:17:03.800
with the discovery of the
general theory of relativity,

00:17:03.800 --> 00:17:08.130
all of this can be written
down in one simple, elegant

00:17:08.130 --> 00:17:11.450
equation, which is this,
Einstein's equation.

00:17:11.450 --> 00:17:14.760
It's a beautiful equation,
again very elegant, very dense,

00:17:14.760 --> 00:17:19.460
very compact in a sense.

00:17:19.460 --> 00:17:22.349
And this equation is
telling us on this side

00:17:22.349 --> 00:17:26.319
here that the shape
space time-- which

00:17:26.319 --> 00:17:28.130
is described by
this symbol here--

00:17:28.130 --> 00:17:33.550
is equal to the matter energy
content on that side here.

00:17:33.550 --> 00:17:35.490
And so what this
equation says in words

00:17:35.490 --> 00:17:40.640
is that space time is bent
by the presence of mass.

00:17:40.640 --> 00:17:45.150
And mass reacts to the shape
of space time in its movement

00:17:45.150 --> 00:17:45.750
through space.

00:17:45.750 --> 00:17:47.583
And so for example,
what this equation tells

00:17:47.583 --> 00:17:50.290
us is that gravity is not the
source like Newton thought

00:17:50.290 --> 00:17:51.540
and like we learned in school.

00:17:51.540 --> 00:17:54.020
Gravity is a consequence of
the geometry of space time.

00:17:54.020 --> 00:17:55.620
And so when we
see the moon going

00:17:55.620 --> 00:17:58.490
around the Earth in a
circular orbit-- or so

00:17:58.490 --> 00:18:01.090
we think-- it's
not a force that's

00:18:01.090 --> 00:18:04.300
keeping this satellite on track.

00:18:04.300 --> 00:18:06.730
What's happening is
the mass of the Earth

00:18:06.730 --> 00:18:09.065
is changing the shape
of space time around it,

00:18:09.065 --> 00:18:11.190
and therefore the moon is
going in a straight path.

00:18:11.190 --> 00:18:15.390
Only a straight path in a bent
space time looks like a circle.

00:18:15.390 --> 00:18:18.830
And this is all beautifully
condensed into this one

00:18:18.830 --> 00:18:20.020
equation.

00:18:20.020 --> 00:18:22.090
And so I was looking
for ways of expressing

00:18:22.090 --> 00:18:26.250
all of that in a way that would
be understandable to people who

00:18:26.250 --> 00:18:28.830
have not studied physics but
are nonetheless fascinated,

00:18:28.830 --> 00:18:30.330
interested by all
of this phenomena.

00:18:30.330 --> 00:18:33.250
After all, the
cosmos is perhaps one

00:18:33.250 --> 00:18:36.970
of the biggest
questions in science.

00:18:36.970 --> 00:18:39.290
Questions such as, where
does the universe come from?

00:18:39.290 --> 00:18:41.240
What will the destiny
of the universe be?

00:18:41.240 --> 00:18:42.990
What is the fundamental
nature of reality?

00:18:42.990 --> 00:18:46.060
These are questions that concern
us all at some very high level.

00:18:46.060 --> 00:18:47.560
But nonetheless,
these are questions

00:18:47.560 --> 00:18:49.660
that fascinate the
public at large.

00:18:49.660 --> 00:18:53.830
So how do we talk about them
in a more immediate way?

00:18:53.830 --> 00:18:56.490
So I was thinking about
all of those things.

00:18:56.490 --> 00:18:59.270
And I'd been thinking about all
of them for a long time now.

00:18:59.270 --> 00:19:02.330
And then one day I
came across something

00:19:02.330 --> 00:19:06.150
that was really impressing
and inspirational.

00:19:06.150 --> 00:19:08.920
I came across the Up Goer Five.

00:19:08.920 --> 00:19:12.210
Now, I probably don't need to
explain to this audience what

00:19:12.210 --> 00:19:16.297
XKCD is, but in case you
are the new Google employee

00:19:16.297 --> 00:19:17.880
that just landed
from Mars and haven't

00:19:17.880 --> 00:19:20.280
heard of XKCD before, I'll
just say a few words about it.

00:19:20.280 --> 00:19:26.730
XKCD is this wildly popular--
geeky, frankly-- geeky cartoon

00:19:26.730 --> 00:19:29.130
on the web, which
is characterized

00:19:29.130 --> 00:19:33.540
by a very peculiar
sense of humor.

00:19:33.540 --> 00:19:36.530
Sometimes those cartoons
are about physics,

00:19:36.530 --> 00:19:37.909
and I get some of those.

00:19:37.909 --> 00:19:39.450
Often they're about
computer science,

00:19:39.450 --> 00:19:41.650
and I don't get many
of those I must admit.

00:19:41.650 --> 00:19:43.025
And sometimes
they're very funny,

00:19:43.025 --> 00:19:45.282
and sometimes
they're just targeted

00:19:45.282 --> 00:19:49.020
at specific communities, and
so you don't get them all.

00:19:49.020 --> 00:19:52.430
But Randall Munroe, the creator
of XKCD a year and a half

00:19:52.430 --> 00:19:55.880
ago or so came up with this
idea of the Up Goer Five.

00:19:55.880 --> 00:19:59.170
As you can see, the Up Goer Five
is none other than the Saturn V

00:19:59.170 --> 00:20:01.920
moon rocket with one
difference, with one twist.

00:20:01.920 --> 00:20:03.790
And the twist was
that Randall thought

00:20:03.790 --> 00:20:07.660
of labeling this
picture of the Saturn V

00:20:07.660 --> 00:20:10.800
with limiting all of the
parts with only the most used

00:20:10.800 --> 00:20:12.930
ten hundred words in
the English language.

00:20:12.930 --> 00:20:16.854
And so of course he couldn't
call it the Saturn V moon

00:20:16.854 --> 00:20:19.020
rocket, because "moon" is
not of the thousand words,

00:20:19.020 --> 00:20:20.620
and "rocket" is not one
of the thousand words,

00:20:20.620 --> 00:20:22.495
and "Saturn's" not one
of the thousand words.

00:20:22.495 --> 00:20:24.540
And so he named it
the Up Good Five.

00:20:24.540 --> 00:20:26.940
And instead of calling
it, NASA's Up Goer Five,

00:20:26.940 --> 00:20:30.490
he called it US Space
Team's Up Goer Five.

00:20:30.490 --> 00:20:30.990
It's funny.

00:20:30.990 --> 00:20:33.140
You should go through
the various parts.

00:20:33.140 --> 00:20:36.650
There are bits and pieces
that read like-- for example,

00:20:36.650 --> 00:20:39.820
here the escape module,
it's called the thing

00:20:39.820 --> 00:20:42.423
to help people escape really
fast if there's a problem

00:20:42.423 --> 00:20:44.506
and everything is on fire
so they decide not to go

00:20:44.506 --> 00:20:46.756
into space, which is a fair--
it's a good description,

00:20:46.756 --> 00:20:47.310
isn't it?

00:20:47.310 --> 00:20:48.950
And if you go down,
down here there's

00:20:48.950 --> 00:20:52.060
the oxygen tank called air
for burning and breathing.

00:20:52.060 --> 00:20:56.040
This part had a very big
problem once, true that.

00:20:56.040 --> 00:20:59.562
And then here the
lunar module is

00:20:59.562 --> 00:21:02.020
the part that flies down to
the other world with two people

00:21:02.020 --> 00:21:03.760
inside, and so on and so forth.

00:21:03.760 --> 00:21:06.260
So it was a fun and
interesting idea.

00:21:06.260 --> 00:21:08.330
And people picked it
up on the internet,

00:21:08.330 --> 00:21:11.530
some people put
together a web page

00:21:11.530 --> 00:21:14.400
where they challenged
users of that web page

00:21:14.400 --> 00:21:17.310
to write up their job
description using this thousand

00:21:17.310 --> 00:21:18.414
words format.

00:21:18.414 --> 00:21:20.330
And so I tried that--
one day I came across it

00:21:20.330 --> 00:21:21.180
and I tried that.

00:21:21.180 --> 00:21:22.920
I spent half an
hour trying write up

00:21:22.920 --> 00:21:27.130
my job as an astrophysicist.

00:21:27.130 --> 00:21:31.470
And it was very hard, much
harder than you would imagine,

00:21:31.470 --> 00:21:33.580
because many, many of words
that you'd like to use

00:21:33.580 --> 00:21:34.556
are not on the list.

00:21:34.556 --> 00:21:36.972
And it was quite surprising
to go through the list and see

00:21:36.972 --> 00:21:39.450
which words are on
it and which aren't.

00:21:39.450 --> 00:21:42.240
And so I wrote up that piece,
maybe a couple paragraphs.

00:21:42.240 --> 00:21:45.670
It took me maybe the best
part of an hour to do so.

00:21:45.670 --> 00:21:48.570
I put it on my website and
then I forgot about it.

00:21:48.570 --> 00:21:50.410
And then a few
weeks later, I was

00:21:50.410 --> 00:21:52.090
giving a talk in
the White Building

00:21:52.090 --> 00:21:55.420
in East London, which is an art
venue near the Olympic Park.

00:21:55.420 --> 00:21:58.710
And the person who introduced me
said a few words about myself.

00:21:58.710 --> 00:22:03.250
And they said that I
also had written my job

00:22:03.250 --> 00:22:04.890
up using the thousand
most used words.

00:22:04.890 --> 00:22:06.070
And they left it at that.

00:22:06.070 --> 00:22:06.810
I gave my talk.

00:22:06.810 --> 00:22:09.880
And at the end of the Q&amp;A
session with the audience,

00:22:09.880 --> 00:22:11.650
somebody asked a
question about, what

00:22:11.650 --> 00:22:13.380
was this business
with 1,000 words.

00:22:13.380 --> 00:22:15.430
I didn't understand what
this thing is about,

00:22:15.430 --> 00:22:16.120
can you explain?

00:22:16.120 --> 00:22:17.950
And so because I had
it on my computer,

00:22:17.950 --> 00:22:20.560
I read it allowed
to the audience.

00:22:20.560 --> 00:22:23.640
And I read out what I'd
written in this format.

00:22:23.640 --> 00:22:26.000
And this was what I had.

00:22:27.340 --> 00:22:30.280
I study tiny bits of matter
that are all around us that we

00:22:30.280 --> 00:22:33.875
cannot see, which
we call dark matter.

00:22:33.875 --> 00:22:36.000
We know dark matter is out
there because it changes

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:38.990
the way other big
far away things move

00:22:38.990 --> 00:22:41.250
such a stars and star crowds.

00:22:41.250 --> 00:22:42.990
We want to understand
what dark matter is

00:22:42.990 --> 00:22:45.281
made of because it could tell
us about where everything

00:22:45.281 --> 00:22:47.290
around us came from and
what will happen next.

00:22:48.326 --> 00:22:49.700
To study dark
matter, people like

00:22:49.700 --> 00:22:52.640
me use big things that have
taken lots of money, thought,

00:22:52.640 --> 00:22:54.280
and people to build.

00:22:54.280 --> 00:22:56.660
Some of the things
fly way above us.

00:22:56.660 --> 00:22:59.070
Some are deep inside the ground.

00:22:59.070 --> 00:23:02.460
Some are large rings that make
tiny pieces of mobile matter

00:23:02.460 --> 00:23:05.870
kiss each other as they fly
around very, very fast, almost

00:23:05.870 --> 00:23:06.790
as fast as light.

00:23:07.980 --> 00:23:10.534
We hope that we can hear
the whisper of dark matter

00:23:10.534 --> 00:23:11.700
if we listen very carefully.

00:23:12.867 --> 00:23:15.200
We take all the whispers from
all the [INAUDIBLE] things

00:23:15.200 --> 00:23:16.949
and we put them together
in our computers.

00:23:17.720 --> 00:23:20.060
We use big computers
to do this, as there

00:23:20.060 --> 00:23:22.560
are lots and lots of tiny
whispers we need to look at.

00:23:23.670 --> 00:23:25.220
I go to places
all over the world

00:23:25.220 --> 00:23:27.530
to talk to other people
like me, as together we

00:23:27.530 --> 00:23:29.980
can think better
and work faster.

00:23:29.980 --> 00:23:32.230
Together perhaps, we can
even find new better ways

00:23:32.230 --> 00:23:34.210
to listen to dark matter.

00:23:34.210 --> 00:23:36.420
Most of them are good people,
and after we've talked,

00:23:36.420 --> 00:23:39.410
we go out and have a
drink, and talk some more.

00:23:39.410 --> 00:23:42.550
So I read this aloud,
and I was astonished

00:23:42.550 --> 00:23:45.960
by the reaction of the
public because everybody

00:23:45.960 --> 00:23:47.950
was taken aback by this format.

00:23:47.950 --> 00:23:50.150
They weren't expecting
it to be quite like that.

00:23:50.150 --> 00:23:54.370
And so I got a very warm round
of applause, which was actually

00:23:54.370 --> 00:23:56.930
much better than the applause
that I got for my talk.

00:23:56.930 --> 00:23:59.555
I was encouraged by
it, because I thought,

00:23:59.555 --> 00:24:01.690
well actually
there is something.

00:24:01.690 --> 00:24:04.920
Perhaps this format is just
what I was looking for.

00:24:04.920 --> 00:24:08.680
Perhaps in this thousand words
there is something hidden

00:24:08.680 --> 00:24:10.990
and it would be an
interesting and fun challenge

00:24:10.990 --> 00:24:14.880
to try to describe the
entirety of all there is.

00:24:14.880 --> 00:24:16.530
Of course, universe
is not on the list,

00:24:16.530 --> 00:24:19.765
so the universe became the all
there is with this format here.

00:24:19.765 --> 00:24:22.030
And so that's what
I started doing.

00:24:22.030 --> 00:24:24.000
I started sitting
down, and I tried

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:26.420
to see whether this format
could be expanded beyond three

00:24:26.420 --> 00:24:29.340
paragraphs to book length.

00:24:29.340 --> 00:24:32.610
And again, I was very
lucky because a few months

00:24:32.610 --> 00:24:37.074
after that, in April, I
had time to spend here

00:24:37.074 --> 00:24:38.990
at the University of
California Santa Barbara.

00:24:38.990 --> 00:24:41.124
And that is the view
out of my office window.

00:24:41.124 --> 00:24:43.040
So The Edge of the Sky,
the title of the book,

00:24:43.040 --> 00:24:46.500
probably came out
of this moment here

00:24:46.500 --> 00:24:50.240
that I was so lucky to have
a three month long research

00:24:50.240 --> 00:24:52.220
stay at Santa Barbara.

00:24:52.220 --> 00:24:54.770
And so I had time and
intellectual freedom

00:24:54.770 --> 00:24:57.360
to do research, of course,
but also to devote myself

00:24:57.360 --> 00:24:59.510
a little bit to
exploring this format

00:24:59.510 --> 00:25:01.690
and to explore the
thousand words idea.

00:25:01.690 --> 00:25:03.440
And to see whether
it could be stretched

00:25:03.440 --> 00:25:05.750
to encompass the all there is.

00:25:05.750 --> 00:25:07.910
And so all of a
sudden I find myself

00:25:07.910 --> 00:25:10.760
battling against this
self-imposed lexicon,

00:25:10.760 --> 00:25:12.024
this straitjacket.

00:25:12.024 --> 00:25:13.440
There were many,
many words that I

00:25:13.440 --> 00:25:15.740
would have liked to use to
describe the universe which

00:25:15.740 --> 00:25:16.770
I didn't have.

00:25:16.770 --> 00:25:20.790
And so I started banging
my head against it.

00:25:20.790 --> 00:25:24.330
I wanted to explain in entire
history and entire knowledge

00:25:24.330 --> 00:25:26.930
of the universe, but without
using the word "universe".

00:25:26.930 --> 00:25:29.600
Without using the word
"gravity", or "telescope",

00:25:29.600 --> 00:25:31.740
or "particle", or "earth".

00:25:31.740 --> 00:25:33.570
"Planet" was not on
the list. "Energy",

00:25:33.570 --> 00:25:35.060
so there wasn't even "energy".

00:25:35.060 --> 00:25:36.910
"Cosmos", of course not.

00:25:36.910 --> 00:25:38.620
"Big Bang" wasn't on the list.

00:25:38.620 --> 00:25:40.887
"Galaxy", "scientist".

00:25:40.887 --> 00:25:42.720
I couldn't talk about
science nor scientist.

00:25:42.720 --> 00:25:44.440
Nor the moon was on the list.

00:25:44.440 --> 00:25:46.120
And not even fog
was on the list,

00:25:46.120 --> 00:25:47.780
which is an important
word for people

00:25:47.780 --> 00:25:49.000
who live in the Bay Area.

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:50.610
They talk about
fog all the time.

00:25:50.610 --> 00:25:52.910
And you think, but why do I need
fog to describe the universe?

00:25:52.910 --> 00:25:54.576
But it turns out that
the early universe

00:25:54.576 --> 00:25:56.924
can be described as a sort
of fog, high energy fog.

00:25:56.924 --> 00:25:58.840
But I couldn't use energy,
I couldn't use fog.

00:25:58.840 --> 00:26:01.800
I could use high, but
that's not very good, right?

00:26:01.800 --> 00:26:04.990
So what I needed to do
was to try and invent

00:26:04.990 --> 00:26:07.820
a new set of vocabulary
really to be talking

00:26:07.820 --> 00:26:11.930
about all there is with a
very different set of words.

00:26:11.930 --> 00:26:14.820
And little by little a
new voice came together.

00:26:14.820 --> 00:26:18.360
A voice that sort of came
out of the challenge itself.

00:26:18.360 --> 00:26:21.040
And the book has
its own voice that

00:26:21.040 --> 00:26:23.300
was a co-creation between
what I wanted to say

00:26:23.300 --> 00:26:24.850
and what the lexicon--
the thousand word list--

00:26:24.850 --> 00:26:25.640
allowed me to say.

00:26:25.640 --> 00:26:29.310
And so a telescope
became a big seer.

00:26:29.310 --> 00:26:31.430
The universe became
the all there is.

00:26:31.430 --> 00:26:34.080
And plants became crazy
stars because they

00:26:34.080 --> 00:26:36.340
go around projecting
motion on the sky.

00:26:36.340 --> 00:26:38.720
The pattern of motion in
the sky is back and forth.

00:26:38.720 --> 00:26:39.970
And so it's a crazy star.

00:26:39.970 --> 00:26:42.750
It doesn't go around
like all of the stars.

00:26:42.750 --> 00:26:44.860
Particles became drops.

00:26:44.860 --> 00:26:48.180
Our planet, the Earth,
became our home world.

00:26:48.180 --> 00:26:51.120
And scientists are
student people,

00:26:51.120 --> 00:26:52.870
or student persons in the book.

00:26:54.470 --> 00:26:56.580
The moon is the sun's sister.

00:26:56.580 --> 00:26:58.600
Sun is on the list,
so I could use that.

00:26:58.600 --> 00:27:00.950
And galaxies are star crowds.

00:27:00.950 --> 00:27:04.460
Now, the Big Bang
was easy, I thought,

00:27:04.460 --> 00:27:07.450
because I can't use a
bang but I can use flash.

00:27:08.700 --> 00:27:12.352
And it was a hot beginning,
so I'll call it the hot flash.

00:27:12.352 --> 00:27:14.560
But then my editor told me
that the hot flash was not

00:27:14.560 --> 00:27:16.000
a good word to use for that.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:19.284
And so I changed it to big
flash, so I learned something.

00:27:19.284 --> 00:27:20.700
And so out of this
new vocabulary,

00:27:20.700 --> 00:27:21.550
a new voice emerged.

00:27:21.550 --> 00:27:23.490
A new way of looking at
the universe emerged.

00:27:23.490 --> 00:27:28.730
And here, at the end of the
book, here's the cloud of words

00:27:28.730 --> 00:27:30.525
that I ended up using.

00:27:30.525 --> 00:27:32.630
707 words all together.

00:27:32.630 --> 00:27:34.670
And you can see that
there's lots of dark,

00:27:34.670 --> 00:27:37.169
because there's lots of dark
stuff in the book, dark energy,

00:27:37.169 --> 00:27:37.780
dark matter.

00:27:37.780 --> 00:27:38.820
Of course, the dark energy
is not called. that.

00:27:38.820 --> 00:27:40.060
It's called the dark push.

00:27:40.060 --> 00:27:42.599
People are mostly
student people,

00:27:42.599 --> 00:27:43.640
that's to say scientists.

00:27:43.640 --> 00:27:45.170
Drops for particles.

00:27:45.170 --> 00:27:48.770
Away, far away is big, because
there's lots of faraway things.

00:27:48.770 --> 00:27:53.660
Light, space, crazy-- for crazy
stars-- seer-- for big seer--

00:27:53.660 --> 00:27:54.600
and so on.

00:27:54.600 --> 00:27:57.080
And so really it becomes
a different language.

00:27:57.080 --> 00:27:58.810
It's almost like
creating a new language

00:27:58.810 --> 00:28:01.610
to talk about the things.

00:28:01.610 --> 00:28:04.490
So today what I
want to do, I want

00:28:04.490 --> 00:28:08.690
to share some of the bits of
the voice that came out of this

00:28:08.690 --> 00:28:11.000
and also share some of the
science that's behind it.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:14.730
But before I do so,
I wanted to give you

00:28:14.730 --> 00:28:17.210
a little condensed
version of the book.

00:28:17.210 --> 00:28:19.120
Each of the 10
chapters of the book

00:28:19.120 --> 00:28:23.260
begins with a very short
haiku style three-liner

00:28:23.260 --> 00:28:24.090
form of poetry.

00:28:24.090 --> 00:28:26.720
So haiku is this
Japanese form of poetry

00:28:26.720 --> 00:28:30.090
which is condensed in just
three verses, which is often

00:28:30.090 --> 00:28:34.270
very imagery heavy
and very condensed.

00:28:34.270 --> 00:28:36.990
And so it's just
a flash of words

00:28:36.990 --> 00:28:38.280
that tries to evoke something.

00:28:38.280 --> 00:28:40.400
And so I tried to
condense each chapter down

00:28:40.400 --> 00:28:41.840
to just three lines.

00:28:41.840 --> 00:28:43.570
And so there is 10 chapters.

00:28:43.570 --> 00:28:46.020
And so in 85 words,
think of this

00:28:46.020 --> 00:28:48.440
as the pseudo code to
the book if you like.

00:28:48.440 --> 00:28:50.970
So that's a double-condensed
version of the universe.

00:28:50.970 --> 00:28:53.470
So the book contains 707 words.

00:28:53.470 --> 00:28:56.335
But actually, here is the
entire [INAUDIBLE] universe

00:28:56.335 --> 00:28:59.610
in 85 words in this
double-condensed form.

00:29:00.950 --> 00:29:05.000
"In the clear night, her
dark hair mirrors the stars.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:08.840
Blue worlds going
around, points of light.

00:29:08.840 --> 00:29:11.895
Behind the stars, space
time grows silent.

00:29:13.160 --> 00:29:16.190
Hot kisses leave
light very tired.

00:29:17.330 --> 00:29:20.685
Her pink lips stay dry
in the heavy dark rain.

00:29:22.020 --> 00:29:24.875
A soft song might
tell you dark stories.

00:29:26.270 --> 00:29:28.340
With the last breath,
and blushing of light

00:29:28.340 --> 00:29:29.255
from faraway stars.

00:29:30.760 --> 00:29:33.580
A silent end, times of
light half remembered.

00:29:34.910 --> 00:29:37.620
So many worlds,
all that can be is.

00:29:38.880 --> 00:29:42.880
Everything opens at the
