00:29:42.880 --> 00:29:44.621
So that's the
[INAUDIBLE] of all there

00:29:44.621 --> 00:29:47.120
is, the entire contents of the
book boiled down to 85 words.

00:29:47.120 --> 00:29:49.120
It might be a little
bit too dense,

00:29:49.120 --> 00:29:53.320
so let me unpack it for
you, and step back, and just

00:29:53.320 --> 00:29:56.080
tell you a little bit the
storyline of the book.

00:29:56.080 --> 00:29:59.740
Because the book story
came out as a conversation,

00:29:59.740 --> 00:30:02.620
really, as a distillation
of hundreds of talks

00:30:02.620 --> 00:30:04.146
that I'd given
before-- public talks

00:30:04.146 --> 00:30:07.300
that I've given to all sorts of
people in different settings.

00:30:07.300 --> 00:30:09.920
So the story came
very naturally to me.

00:30:09.920 --> 00:30:12.750
I was very lucky that
I had already in mind

00:30:12.750 --> 00:30:15.680
when I started writing the
book what I wanted to tell.

00:30:15.680 --> 00:30:20.480
And it's a story that begins
with a student woman--

00:30:20.480 --> 00:30:25.235
a fictional character-- here
she is, walking up to big seer.

00:30:25.235 --> 00:30:27.110
There are two characters
really in this book.

00:30:27.110 --> 00:30:32.150
One is the student woman who is
a student person who goes out

00:30:32.150 --> 00:30:35.420
for the first time to one of
the biggest telescopes on earth,

00:30:35.420 --> 00:30:38.540
big seer, for a
night of observation

00:30:38.540 --> 00:30:42.230
to study dark matter and try to
crack the dark matter mystery.

00:30:42.230 --> 00:30:44.370
So here she is
walking up to big seer

00:30:44.370 --> 00:30:49.160
in this beautiful illustration
that accompanies the book.

00:30:49.160 --> 00:30:51.050
I was very lucky
to have [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:51.050 --> 00:30:55.110
a very talented young
artist and illustrator

00:30:55.110 --> 00:30:59.480
who produced and created the
beautiful line drawings that

00:30:59.480 --> 00:31:01.000
accompany the book.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:04.990
And so, our student person,
she goes up to big seer.

00:31:04.990 --> 00:31:07.090
Big seer is the second
character in his book.

00:31:07.090 --> 00:31:09.650
It's the silent helper,
it's the big telescope

00:31:09.650 --> 00:31:11.562
that helps her in
trying to unlock

00:31:11.562 --> 00:31:12.770
the mysteries of dark matter.

00:31:12.770 --> 00:31:14.769
So it's like a fictionalized
version of reality.

00:31:14.769 --> 00:31:17.090
Of course, in reality
scientists do not

00:31:17.090 --> 00:31:20.590
go out to telescopes on top
of mountains like Hawaii,

00:31:20.590 --> 00:31:23.150
for example, working
alone at 12,000 feet

00:31:23.150 --> 00:31:24.840
because that
wouldn't be possible.

00:31:24.840 --> 00:31:29.060
But still, that's a
fictional version of reality

00:31:29.060 --> 00:31:33.140
that allows us to follow
her night of observation

00:31:33.140 --> 00:31:36.590
and her questions about the
all there is, the way it became

00:31:36.590 --> 00:31:39.520
to be what it is today and all
the questions that we still

00:31:39.520 --> 00:31:43.347
have about its nature
and its properties.

00:31:43.347 --> 00:31:44.930
She in particular
is out there looking

00:31:44.930 --> 00:31:47.179
for that matter, which is
one of the biggest mysteries

00:31:47.179 --> 00:31:49.290
today and one that
can be probably solved

00:31:49.290 --> 00:31:52.750
by science in the next five
years or so, or so we hope.

00:31:52.750 --> 00:31:57.340
So our scientist goes out and
makes observations of the sky.

00:31:57.340 --> 00:31:59.680
And what is she looking for?

00:31:59.680 --> 00:32:01.320
Let's take a step back.

00:32:01.320 --> 00:32:06.260
Here is a picture of
Edwin Hubble, 1927,

00:32:06.260 --> 00:32:09.324
the discover of what is
now called Hubble's Law.

00:32:09.324 --> 00:32:10.990
The fact that the
universe is expanding,

00:32:10.990 --> 00:32:15.880
which Hubble discovered
by looking at distant star

00:32:15.880 --> 00:32:17.679
crowds-- that's to say galaxies.

00:32:17.679 --> 00:32:19.220
At the time they
were called nebulae.

00:32:19.220 --> 00:32:20.275
People didn't know
what they were.

00:32:20.275 --> 00:32:22.920
They didn't even know whether
they were inside or outside

00:32:22.920 --> 00:32:26.020
the wide world-- that's to say
the Milky Way, our own galaxy.

00:32:26.020 --> 00:32:30.550
But what Hubble discovered
was that he charted out

00:32:30.550 --> 00:32:35.060
the velocity of those
distant star crowds

00:32:35.060 --> 00:32:37.690
as a function of the
distance from us.

00:32:37.690 --> 00:32:39.990
And so each one of those
dots is a measurement

00:32:39.990 --> 00:32:44.770
that he took working
not far away from here

00:32:44.770 --> 00:32:46.140
in southern California.

00:32:46.140 --> 00:32:51.630
And what he saw, he realized
that as objects are further

00:32:51.630 --> 00:32:55.210
away from us here, they're
also traveling at faster speeds

00:32:55.210 --> 00:32:56.695
and are receding from us.

00:32:56.695 --> 00:32:58.010
They're moving away from us.

00:32:58.010 --> 00:33:00.405
And what he did, he
very boldly drew a line

00:33:00.405 --> 00:33:02.720
through those points
and said, here

00:33:02.720 --> 00:33:04.170
there is a linear relationship.

00:33:04.170 --> 00:33:06.680
There is a relationship between
how far away objects are

00:33:06.680 --> 00:33:08.250
and how far they're moving.

00:33:08.250 --> 00:33:11.765
And the slope of this line here,
the slope of this relationship

00:33:11.765 --> 00:33:14.460
is to do is day
called Hubble's Law.

00:33:14.460 --> 00:33:18.980
And this Hubble's Law is telling
us that far away galaxies

00:33:18.980 --> 00:33:22.290
are moving away from us
faster than nearby galaxies.

00:33:22.290 --> 00:33:25.900
And this is only possible if the
entire universe is expanding.

00:33:25.900 --> 00:33:28.575
In other words, the picture
that emerged from this discovery

00:33:28.575 --> 00:33:31.602
is that galaxies are moving
away from each other.

00:33:31.602 --> 00:33:33.560
And they're moving away
faster the further away

00:33:33.560 --> 00:33:35.280
they are as a
consequence of the fact

00:33:35.280 --> 00:33:38.180
that space time itself between
galaxies is stretching.

00:33:38.180 --> 00:33:41.950
It's expanding just like the
pizza dough that we saw before.

00:33:41.950 --> 00:33:43.810
But the astonishing
thing is that if we now

00:33:43.810 --> 00:33:48.090
turn this thing upside down and
we look at time going backwards

00:33:48.090 --> 00:33:49.950
in the backwards
direction, he thinks

00:33:49.950 --> 00:33:52.960
if galaxies are moving
away from each other today,

00:33:52.960 --> 00:33:56.230
this means that they were
together in the past--

00:33:56.230 --> 00:33:57.989
or they were closer
by in the past.

00:33:57.989 --> 00:33:59.780
And if you go even
further back in the past

00:33:59.780 --> 00:34:00.863
they were closer together.

00:34:00.863 --> 00:34:02.860
And if you can go even
further back in time,

00:34:02.860 --> 00:34:05.660
there comes a point where all
these galaxies were heaped up

00:34:05.660 --> 00:34:08.850
on top of each other, which
is what we call the Big Bang.

00:34:08.850 --> 00:34:10.670
So the astonishing
discovery that Hubble

00:34:10.670 --> 00:34:12.710
made almost 100
years ago now was

00:34:12.710 --> 00:34:14.170
that the universe is expanding.

00:34:14.170 --> 00:34:17.870
And it all came from an
initial hot, dense point

00:34:17.870 --> 00:34:19.580
that we now call the Big Bang.

00:34:20.947 --> 00:34:22.530
And so this was what
Hubble discovered

00:34:22.530 --> 00:34:24.620
with only a handful
of observations,

00:34:24.620 --> 00:34:26.580
maybe 30, 40
galaxies he measured.

00:34:26.580 --> 00:34:27.270
That's all.

00:34:27.270 --> 00:34:29.590
But nowadays of
course, our discipline

00:34:29.590 --> 00:34:31.570
has moved on very much.

00:34:31.570 --> 00:34:34.150
And so we are very
much entering the world

00:34:34.150 --> 00:34:36.560
of big data, which is
something that people here

00:34:36.560 --> 00:34:37.830
know a lot about of course.

00:34:37.830 --> 00:34:40.820
And so you can see
here, this graph

00:34:40.820 --> 00:34:44.820
is an extension of what
Hubble saw in 1927.

00:34:44.820 --> 00:34:47.240
So Hubble only saw
this little corner here

00:34:47.240 --> 00:34:52.380
of this diagram where he put
that line through these dots.

00:34:52.380 --> 00:34:54.257
We have been now able
to extend this diagram

00:34:54.257 --> 00:34:55.340
to much further distances.

00:34:55.340 --> 00:34:57.730
And that's a picture
from the paper

00:34:57.730 --> 00:35:01.160
that I quoted in the beginning,
the 1999 [INAUDIBLE] paper that

00:35:01.160 --> 00:35:04.910
was awarded the Nobel Prize
for physics a few years ago.

00:35:04.910 --> 00:35:06.740
And this was the status in 1999.

00:35:06.740 --> 00:35:10.030
In 2010 you can see how many
more data points we have,

00:35:10.030 --> 00:35:13.090
and how this expansion
of the universe

00:35:13.090 --> 00:35:16.070
is being charted out with
greater and greater precision.

00:35:16.070 --> 00:35:18.740
Here are observations of the
relic radiation from the Big

00:35:18.740 --> 00:35:22.210
Bang, the remnants
of the Big Bang.

00:35:22.210 --> 00:35:27.190
In 1994 the discovery of the
microwave echo of the Big Bang

00:35:27.190 --> 00:35:28.200
with the COBE satellite.

00:35:28.200 --> 00:35:29.860
Again, Nobel Prize for physics.

00:35:29.860 --> 00:35:34.450
2001 the WMAP satellite
measures the same radiation

00:35:34.450 --> 00:35:36.130
but with a much
higher resolution.

00:35:36.130 --> 00:35:38.600
And now the Planck satellite,
the latest instrument,

00:35:38.600 --> 00:35:41.360
has observed the sky with
even greater resolution.

00:35:41.360 --> 00:35:42.880
We can see how many
more details we

00:35:42.880 --> 00:35:45.130
can see from this light
that comes straight

00:35:45.130 --> 00:35:46.460
from the Big Bang.

00:35:46.460 --> 00:35:48.540
Here galaxies in the sky.

00:35:48.540 --> 00:35:52.420
In 1985 there was a state of
the art 1,100 galaxies observed.

00:35:52.420 --> 00:35:55.091
Each one of those dots
is a galaxy on the sky.

00:35:55.091 --> 00:35:57.590
And this is the state of the
art today, one million galaxies

00:35:57.590 --> 00:35:59.170
from the [INAUDIBLE] Sky Survey.

00:35:59.170 --> 00:36:01.690
Each one of those
colored dots is a galaxy.

00:36:01.690 --> 00:36:03.250
And when the square
kilometer array

00:36:03.250 --> 00:36:06.470
comes online in
about 10 years time--

00:36:06.470 --> 00:36:10.320
which will be an array of
radio telescope spread over two

00:36:10.320 --> 00:36:14.520
continents-- we'll measure
the position and distance

00:36:14.520 --> 00:36:16.680
of tens of millions of
galaxies in the sky.

00:36:16.680 --> 00:36:20.510
So this is what big data
now means in our field.

00:36:20.510 --> 00:36:21.810
And what have we learned?

00:36:21.810 --> 00:36:24.660
So let's have a look
at a patch of the sky.

00:36:24.660 --> 00:36:27.270
Let's have a look at the
patch of the sky which

00:36:27.270 --> 00:36:28.390
is pictured here.

00:36:28.390 --> 00:36:30.181
So you can see here,
there's the full moon.

00:36:30.181 --> 00:36:32.330
The full moon is about
half a degree on the sky

00:36:32.330 --> 00:36:34.950
if you look at it from here.

00:36:34.950 --> 00:36:36.990
And everybody knows
what the full moon

00:36:36.990 --> 00:36:38.480
looks like on the sky.

00:36:38.480 --> 00:36:40.820
And here is a little
patch of that same sky

00:36:40.820 --> 00:36:44.730
in which is singled
out this yellow square.

00:36:44.730 --> 00:36:46.750
So this is a tiny
little patch of the sky.

00:36:46.750 --> 00:36:50.420
To give you an idea of how
small this yellow square is,

00:36:50.420 --> 00:36:52.485
it is the same
amount of sky that

00:36:52.485 --> 00:36:56.605
would fit inside the eye of a
needle held at arm's length.

00:36:56.605 --> 00:36:58.440
So it's tiny.

00:36:58.440 --> 00:37:01.840
And yet if you look at it with
the most powerful telescopes

00:37:01.840 --> 00:37:04.130
that we have, the
Hubble Space Telescope,

00:37:04.130 --> 00:37:05.750
this is what you see.

00:37:05.750 --> 00:37:10.390
There are 505,000 galaxies
inside that eye of the needle.

00:37:10.390 --> 00:37:12.790
And each one of those galaxies
contains about 100 billion

00:37:12.790 --> 00:37:15.690
stars, just like the
Milky Way, our galaxy,

00:37:15.690 --> 00:37:18.926
contains about a few
hundred billion stars.

00:37:18.926 --> 00:37:21.300
And if I zoom in, you can see
that each one of those dots

00:37:21.300 --> 00:37:22.337
indeed is a galaxy.

00:37:22.337 --> 00:37:23.920
You can see beautiful
spiral galaxies,

00:37:23.920 --> 00:37:26.670
and you can see other more
regularly shaped galaxies,

00:37:26.670 --> 00:37:27.694
and so on and so forth.

00:37:27.694 --> 00:37:29.110
And so all of those
galaxies, they

00:37:29.110 --> 00:37:31.130
fit within this eye of a needle.

00:37:31.130 --> 00:37:32.870
So you can imagine
how many more there

00:37:32.870 --> 00:37:35.790
are in the entire universe
as we cover the entire sky.

00:37:35.790 --> 00:37:38.210
And yet, perhaps the most
astonishing discovery

00:37:38.210 --> 00:37:41.220
of modern cosmology
is that this is only

00:37:41.220 --> 00:37:42.690
a fraction of what is out there.

00:37:42.690 --> 00:37:46.020
So the headline news is
that 96% of the universe

00:37:46.020 --> 00:37:47.870
is actually missing.

00:37:47.870 --> 00:37:51.030
So what is this dark
side of the universe?

00:37:51.030 --> 00:37:54.890
What is all the rest that's
out there that does not show up

00:37:54.890 --> 00:37:58.100
in that picture and doesn't
show up in any of the pictures?

00:37:58.100 --> 00:38:02.432
Well, we now know that the
luminous matter-- stars

00:38:02.432 --> 00:38:04.390
and luminous galaxies--
this tiny little sliver

00:38:04.390 --> 00:38:08.150
of the cosmic sky, this
tiny little bit here,

00:38:08.150 --> 00:38:10.290
all the rest here,
the red bit here

00:38:10.290 --> 00:38:12.145
is other non-luminous
components in the form

00:38:12.145 --> 00:38:14.162
of intergalactic
gas, and neutrinos,

00:38:14.162 --> 00:38:16.120
and super massive black
holes, and so on, which

00:38:16.120 --> 00:38:17.947
is all stuff that's
made of particles that

00:38:17.947 --> 00:38:20.950
are the same kind of particles
that we are made off.

00:38:20.950 --> 00:38:23.280
So this part here is the
tiny fraction of the universe

00:38:23.280 --> 00:38:24.660
that we know about.

00:38:24.660 --> 00:38:27.980
But the largest
majority of the universe

00:38:27.980 --> 00:38:31.630
is made of dark, invisible,
unknown, as of yet undiscovered

00:38:31.630 --> 00:38:32.130
stuff.

00:38:32.130 --> 00:38:37.530
Dark matter 23% or so of
the universe and dark energy

00:38:37.530 --> 00:38:40.529
the biggest part of the pie.

00:38:40.529 --> 00:38:42.070
What in the book is
called dark push.

00:38:43.080 --> 00:38:45.830
And so one of the biggest
mysteries of cosmology

00:38:45.830 --> 00:38:49.300
is precisely to try and work out
what this 95% of the universe

00:38:49.300 --> 00:38:50.240
is made of.

00:38:50.240 --> 00:38:52.860
What is the fundamental
nature of all the stuff

00:38:52.860 --> 00:38:54.290
that we don't know about?

00:38:54.290 --> 00:38:57.260
But fortunately,
we now have means

00:38:57.260 --> 00:39:00.390
of doing that with
data, with very

00:39:00.390 --> 00:39:01.560
sophisticated observations.

00:39:01.560 --> 00:39:04.620
Remember, cosmology
is a time machine.

00:39:04.620 --> 00:39:07.160
In other words, the
speed of light is finite.

00:39:07.160 --> 00:39:09.380
And being finite, it means
that the further out you

00:39:09.380 --> 00:39:12.310
look in the universe, the
further back in time you see.

00:39:12.310 --> 00:39:14.960
Because light takes time
to travel from the furthest

00:39:14.960 --> 00:39:16.390
objects to us.

00:39:16.390 --> 00:39:18.750
300,000 kilometers per
second is the speed of light,

00:39:18.750 --> 00:39:20.710
so every time you look at the
sun, you're looking at the sun

00:39:20.710 --> 00:39:22.860
not as it is now but
you're looking at the sun

00:39:22.860 --> 00:39:25.970
as it was eight minutes ago
because that's how long it

00:39:25.970 --> 00:39:28.571
takes for light to cover the 150
million kilometers between us

00:39:28.571 --> 00:39:29.070
and the sun.

00:39:29.070 --> 00:39:30.630
So if you look at
distant galaxies,

00:39:30.630 --> 00:39:33.030
you see them not as they
are "now", quote, unquote,

00:39:33.030 --> 00:39:35.020
but as they were
billions of years

00:39:35.020 --> 00:39:37.470
ago when that light first left.

00:39:37.470 --> 00:39:42.257
And so if you look back
further out in space,

00:39:42.257 --> 00:39:43.840
if you use the Hubble
Space Telescope,

00:39:43.840 --> 00:39:47.770
that's pretty much how far back
in space and time we can look,

00:39:47.770 --> 00:39:48.880
a few billion years ago.

00:39:48.880 --> 00:39:52.100
But if you use different types
of light, like microwave light

00:39:52.100 --> 00:39:56.950
and microwave satellites, we
can go back all the way almost

00:39:56.950 --> 00:39:58.340
to the Big Bang.

00:39:58.340 --> 00:40:03.180
And so we can pick up light
that left just 380,000 years

00:40:03.180 --> 00:40:06.900
after the Big Bang, which is
the end of the visible universe.

00:40:06.900 --> 00:40:09.250
And this is what we see.

00:40:09.250 --> 00:40:11.700
This is a picture of the
sky taken in microwaves.

00:40:11.700 --> 00:40:13.800
And that's a picture that
shows the baby universe.

00:40:13.800 --> 00:40:15.810
This light left
when the universe

00:40:15.810 --> 00:40:18.490
was a tiny, tiny fraction
of its current age.

00:40:18.490 --> 00:40:21.520
The current age of the universe
is about 13.7 billion years,

00:40:21.520 --> 00:40:24.290
and this light has
been en route almost

00:40:24.290 --> 00:40:25.360
since the very beginning.

00:40:25.360 --> 00:40:26.910
And what you see
here is a picture

00:40:26.910 --> 00:40:30.090
of the universe where
there are no galaxies yet,

00:40:30.090 --> 00:40:32.160
because there was no time
for galaxies to form.

00:40:32.160 --> 00:40:33.500
No stars yet.

00:40:33.500 --> 00:40:38.870
All there is is matter, light,
photons, and dark matter.

00:40:38.870 --> 00:40:40.520
What you see here
is the red spots

00:40:40.520 --> 00:40:44.450
are spots of slightly larger
concentration of energy,

00:40:44.450 --> 00:40:49.470
and light, and matter, which
are the seeds of what then will

00:40:49.470 --> 00:40:52.250
become galaxies such
as the Milky Way.

00:40:52.250 --> 00:40:55.374
And so this picture here is the
end of the visible universe.

00:40:55.374 --> 00:40:56.790
And I don't mean
it as a metaphor,

00:40:56.790 --> 00:40:59.804
I mean it as a
scientific statement

00:40:59.804 --> 00:41:01.970
because there's no way we
can see past this picture.

00:41:01.970 --> 00:41:06.300
The universe was opaque
to light before this time,

00:41:06.300 --> 00:41:09.440
because it was too energetic
for light to travel freely.

00:41:09.440 --> 00:41:12.340
Light kept bouncing off
electrons and protons

00:41:12.340 --> 00:41:13.350
in the early universe.

00:41:13.350 --> 00:41:17.619
And so this early universe
picture, which we can see,

00:41:17.619 --> 00:41:19.035
can be described
as a sort of fog.

00:41:19.035 --> 00:41:21.820
It was a high energy fog,
2,000 Kelvin temperature.

00:41:21.820 --> 00:41:26.430
So almost 2,000 degrees Celsius.

00:41:26.430 --> 00:41:28.630
But in the book, of course,
I couldn't talk about it

00:41:28.630 --> 00:41:33.580
in terms of fog, because there
is no fog in the list of words.

00:41:33.580 --> 00:41:35.965
So here's how this
early universe picture

00:41:35.965 --> 00:41:38.340
is described using
the thousand words.

00:41:40.080 --> 00:41:43.790
"It was like when you look out
your window on a cold morning.

00:41:43.790 --> 00:41:46.179
There's ice on the road,
and everything looks gray,

00:41:46.179 --> 00:41:47.720
and you can't see
past your driveway.

00:41:48.840 --> 00:41:51.690
This is because light gets
kicked about by tiny water

00:41:51.690 --> 00:41:54.010
drops in the air before
reaching your eyes.

00:41:54.856 --> 00:41:56.230
Something like
this was happening

00:41:56.230 --> 00:41:58.910
at that time", that's to
say, at the very beginning,

00:41:58.910 --> 00:42:03.370
"only everything was 100 times
hotter than on a hot summer's

00:42:03.370 --> 00:42:04.556
day.

00:42:04.556 --> 00:42:06.970
And so this is just
a simple description

00:42:06.970 --> 00:42:09.300
of what the universe looked
like at the very beginning.

00:42:09.300 --> 00:42:11.800
And then things started
to change, and evolve,

00:42:11.800 --> 00:42:13.720
and galaxies grew out of it.

00:42:13.720 --> 00:42:16.420
And gravity started
doing its job.

00:42:16.420 --> 00:42:20.070
And gravity, as I told you
before, is not at all a force.

00:42:20.070 --> 00:42:22.780
It's just a reflection on
the shape of space time.

00:42:22.780 --> 00:42:25.020
So here's how this
can be described

00:42:25.020 --> 00:42:28.330
using the thousand
words lexicon.

00:42:28.330 --> 00:42:31.280
So this is a crash course in
generativity in one paragraph

00:42:31.280 --> 00:42:32.920
and less than 1,000
words in English.

00:42:34.090 --> 00:42:38.730
So talking about Einstein here
and how he thought gravity

00:42:38.730 --> 00:42:41.140
was different from
Newton's gravity.

00:42:41.140 --> 00:42:42.880
"He", that's to
say Mr. Einstein,

00:42:42.880 --> 00:42:44.880
"then asked himself,
what would happen

00:42:44.880 --> 00:42:46.920
if you put some heavy
stuff-- as heavy

00:42:46.920 --> 00:42:49.540
as a star in the
middle of space time?

00:42:49.540 --> 00:42:52.740
He was the first to understand
that matter puts in space

00:42:52.740 --> 00:42:54.770
time and changes
the way it looks.

00:42:54.770 --> 00:42:57.400
In turn, the form
of space time is

00:42:57.400 --> 00:42:59.935
what moves matter
one way or another.

00:42:59.935 --> 00:43:01.810
As an idea, this was
very different from what

00:43:01.810 --> 00:43:03.700
Mr. Newton had said
a long time ago.

00:43:03.700 --> 00:43:06.610
For Mr. Newton, space and time
did not talk to each other,

00:43:06.610 --> 00:43:09.870
never married, and
lived different lives."

00:43:09.870 --> 00:43:12.210
And then it goes on
describing how this idea could

00:43:12.210 --> 00:43:14.900
be tested using a solar
eclipse, because of course

00:43:14.900 --> 00:43:18.030
exceptional claims need
exceptional means of evidence.

00:43:18.030 --> 00:43:21.150
And so in 1919 Einstein's
idea of generativity

00:43:21.150 --> 00:43:24.870
was proven proven right by
observations of a solar eclipse

00:43:24.870 --> 00:43:28.780
here in one of the illustrations
of the book that actually

00:43:28.780 --> 00:43:32.040
proved that light was
being moved around

00:43:32.040 --> 00:43:36.080
and changing trajectory
along the bent space

00:43:36.080 --> 00:43:38.880
time exactly like
Einstein predicted.

00:43:38.880 --> 00:43:44.660
So here is the backdrop of
what the student person is

00:43:44.660 --> 00:43:48.910
trying to do with
our observations.

00:43:48.910 --> 00:43:51.670
And all of these observations
that I told you about,

00:43:51.670 --> 00:43:54.160
they paint a very strange
picture of the universe.

00:43:54.160 --> 00:43:56.560
A picture of the
universe where again we

00:43:56.560 --> 00:43:59.290
have a very puzzling
universe, a universe where

00:43:59.290 --> 00:44:02.850
we have dark matter, again
these omega numbers that make it

00:44:02.850 --> 00:44:05.490
look as if we know what we're
talking about-- but in reality

00:44:05.490 --> 00:44:07.660
we just hide our ignorance
behind Greek letters.

00:44:07.660 --> 00:44:10.930
And so the amount of dark matter
that there is in the universe

00:44:10.930 --> 00:44:12.650
has been now measured
very precisely

00:44:12.650 --> 00:44:14.890
using its gravitational
effect in the cosmos,

00:44:14.890 --> 00:44:19.530
about 26.6% with a
few percent around it.

00:44:19.530 --> 00:44:21.180
And then there's
another, and possibly

00:44:21.180 --> 00:44:23.860
a new type of particle beyond
[INAUDIBLE] particle physics.

00:44:23.860 --> 00:44:26.190
And then there is dark
energy, the dark push,

00:44:26.190 --> 00:44:28.440
the mysterious force that's
making the universe expand

00:44:28.440 --> 00:44:33.610
faster and faster all the time,
which makes up 70% or more

00:44:33.610 --> 00:44:35.979
68.6% of the universe.

00:44:35.979 --> 00:44:38.270
And those two things together
are very much mysterious.

00:44:38.270 --> 00:44:39.436
We don't know what they are.

00:44:40.230 --> 00:44:42.680
One thing we've learned
actually very precisely,

00:44:42.680 --> 00:44:44.290
which is the age
of the universe.

00:44:44.290 --> 00:44:49.280
Now the age of the universe
is 13,798,000 years,

00:44:49.280 --> 00:44:52.200
which is astonishing
to be able to quote

00:44:52.200 --> 00:44:56.850
this figure within a margin of
error of 37 million years only.

00:44:56.850 --> 00:44:58.350
That's nothing at all.

00:44:58.350 --> 00:45:00.744
I mean, we sit on the
earth, it's right here,

00:45:00.744 --> 00:45:03.160
and yet we don't know the age
of the earth with precision.

00:45:03.160 --> 00:45:04.910
And we can tell the
age of the universe

00:45:04.910 --> 00:45:07.000
with incredible accuracy.

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:09.260
It's an accuracy that's
really astonishing.

00:45:09.260 --> 00:45:15.750
Let's put this into
perspective with 1,000 words.

00:45:15.750 --> 00:45:17.560
"This is really
great if you think

00:45:17.560 --> 00:45:19.185
how long ago the
big flash happened.

00:45:20.200 --> 00:45:24.370
It was over 100 times 100
times 100 times 100 times

00:45:24.370 --> 00:45:26.070
100 years ago.

00:45:26.070 --> 00:45:28.600
We know the age of
the order so well

00:45:28.600 --> 00:45:30.420
that it would be like
being able to tell

00:45:30.420 --> 00:45:32.770
the day of the year a
stranger in the street

00:45:32.770 --> 00:45:38.130
came to life to the nearest
day just by looking at him."

00:45:38.130 --> 00:45:42.650
And that's one of the great
discoveries of cosmology

00:45:42.650 --> 00:45:45.310
that comes out of mapping
out the tiny ripples

00:45:45.310 --> 00:45:48.360
in the microwave radiation in
the voluminous echo of the Big

00:45:48.360 --> 00:45:50.330
Bang we were talking
about before.

00:45:50.330 --> 00:45:53.677
And I don't want to go into
details of the technicalities,

00:45:53.677 --> 00:45:55.510
but I do want to show
you one picture that's

00:45:55.510 --> 00:45:57.580
quite astonishing, I think.

00:45:57.580 --> 00:45:59.220
It's slightly
technical, but again I

00:45:59.220 --> 00:46:01.480
think people here will
appreciate the idea of data

00:46:01.480 --> 00:46:04.990
compression and how we can
compress a large amount of data

00:46:04.990 --> 00:46:06.870
into just a few numbers.

00:46:06.870 --> 00:46:10.130
So here we have our micro
satellite sending down

00:46:10.130 --> 00:46:12.870
a stream of data, a
stream of points, 10

00:46:12.870 --> 00:46:16.220
to the 12 bits of data that go
into making this map of the sky

00:46:16.220 --> 00:46:19.030
that I told you before, 50
million pixels that then gets

00:46:19.030 --> 00:46:23.160
reduced by statistical
massaging into a plot which

00:46:23.160 --> 00:46:26.370
has got 2,500
measurements points on it.

00:46:26.370 --> 00:46:28.210
And this plot how much
fluctuations there

00:46:28.210 --> 00:46:29.836
are on this map as
a function of scale.

00:46:29.836 --> 00:46:31.793
It doesn't really matter
the technical details,

00:46:31.793 --> 00:46:33.850
but what I want to
show you is this plot,

00:46:33.850 --> 00:46:36.930
which is derived from the
microwave [INAUDIBLE] map,

00:46:36.930 --> 00:46:38.990
the map of the light
from the Big Bang.

00:46:38.990 --> 00:46:42.690
And you can see the data
points here which are in red.

00:46:42.690 --> 00:46:45.140
And they follow a very
interesting oscillatory

00:46:45.140 --> 00:46:47.340
wave-like pattern,
a pattern that we

00:46:47.340 --> 00:46:50.380
can understand using [INAUDIBLE]
level physics in very

00:46:50.380 --> 00:46:53.160
great detail, because this is
physics of the universe which

00:46:53.160 --> 00:46:56.260
we understand with
very high precision.

00:46:56.260 --> 00:46:59.180
And this is proven by the
fact that we can-- right now

00:46:59.180 --> 00:47:01.865
the theoretical model, a theory
of the universe, of the all

00:47:01.865 --> 00:47:04.850
there is, that contains
three different ingredients.

00:47:04.850 --> 00:47:07.480
One is Einstein
generativity, the other one

00:47:07.480 --> 00:47:09.750
is the Big Bang as a
theory, and the other one

00:47:09.750 --> 00:47:12.420
is these dark components--
dark matter, dark energy,

00:47:12.420 --> 00:47:14.624
or the dark push as I put it.

00:47:14.624 --> 00:47:16.790
And you could see that this
theoretical model, which

00:47:16.790 --> 00:47:19.800
has got only six numbers
in it, six free parameters,

00:47:19.800 --> 00:47:20.987
is the green line.

00:47:20.987 --> 00:47:23.070
It goes through the
observations almost perfectly.

00:47:23.070 --> 00:47:25.370
So we understand the
observation incredibly well,

00:47:25.370 --> 00:47:28.680
all the way if we extend
the horizontal axis,

00:47:28.680 --> 00:47:31.690
we understand them all the
way to the smallest details

00:47:31.690 --> 00:47:36.570
down here, down into this
tail of distribution.

00:47:36.570 --> 00:47:38.350
And so what I want
to say with this

00:47:38.350 --> 00:47:40.520
is that we have this
incredible wealth

00:47:40.520 --> 00:47:41.900
of data about the universe.

00:47:41.900 --> 00:47:44.840
We've got these incredible
sophisticated models.

00:47:44.840 --> 00:47:49.030
And yet, to make them work, to
make the models match the data,

00:47:49.030 --> 00:47:50.935
we need these two
unknown ingredients.

00:47:50.935 --> 00:47:53.460
We need dark matter,
we need dark energy,

00:47:53.460 --> 00:47:55.070
and we don't know what they are.

00:47:55.070 --> 00:47:58.510
And this is one of the
biggest quests at the moment.

00:47:58.510 --> 00:48:00.260
So how does our
student person go

00:48:00.260 --> 00:48:03.670
about understanding dark
matter and dark energy?

00:48:06.430 --> 00:48:09.610
So during her night
of observations

00:48:09.610 --> 00:48:12.480
she is thinking about
those mysteries,

00:48:12.480 --> 00:48:15.330
and how they are
very much unsolved,

00:48:15.330 --> 00:48:17.900
and what we can do to try
and understand them better.

00:48:19.010 --> 00:48:23.420
So when she casts her mind's
eye back to the dark push,

00:48:23.420 --> 00:48:25.850
this is what goes
on in her mind.

00:48:26.940 --> 00:48:28.770
"She steps outside
in the cold night,

00:48:28.770 --> 00:48:31.670
holding her cup of hot
coffee with both hands.

00:48:31.670 --> 00:48:35.130
The wide world is beautiful,
the dark clear sky.

00:48:35.130 --> 00:48:39.260
And once again, she can't
help but be amazed by it all.

00:48:39.260 --> 00:48:41.950
It doesn't matter how many
times she's seen this before

00:48:41.950 --> 00:48:44.570
or how much she knows
about what is out there.

00:48:44.570 --> 00:48:46.965
The site of the stars is
enough to make her gasp.

00:48:48.500 --> 00:48:53.230
It all seems so still, and yet
it's changing all the time,

00:48:53.230 --> 00:48:55.352
she whispers to no one.

00:48:55.352 --> 00:48:57.310
It is hard to believe
that everything out there

00:48:57.310 --> 00:49:00.870
past the wide world and it
starts is running away from us.

00:49:02.230 --> 00:49:05.250
Yet, like Mr. Hubble
found long ago,

00:49:05.250 --> 00:49:07.820
the star crowds are running
away from each other

00:49:07.820 --> 00:49:10.880
at the space between them
gets bigger and bigger.

00:49:10.880 --> 00:49:13.080
The all there is is
growing with time."

00:49:13.080 --> 00:49:16.380
And that's what the dark
push or dark energy is doing.

00:49:16.380 --> 00:49:19.180
A repulsive force,
possibly a new type

00:49:19.180 --> 00:49:22.120
of a vacuum energy-- and energy
associated with empty space

00:49:22.120 --> 00:49:24.120
itself-- that's
pushing things apart.

00:49:24.120 --> 00:49:26.690
And the big mystery is that
this dark energy not only

00:49:26.690 --> 00:49:28.950
is something that we don't
understand fundamentally,

00:49:28.950 --> 00:49:33.640
it's something that could even
be pointing to what I call

00:49:33.640 --> 00:49:40.630
the dark side of the universe
here, because one of the ideas

00:49:40.630 --> 00:49:44.070
to explain the existence
of this dark push

00:49:44.070 --> 00:49:47.090
is to postulate the
existence of a multiverse.

00:49:47.090 --> 00:49:50.340
A grander scheme
of reality in which

00:49:50.340 --> 00:49:54.430
we are but only but a
tiny little bit of what

00:49:54.430 --> 00:49:55.020
is out there.

00:49:55.020 --> 00:49:57.490
So the all there is, all the
stuff that I told you about--

00:49:57.490 --> 00:49:59.073
and this is very
speculative, but it's

00:49:59.073 --> 00:50:01.110
just one of the ideas
that can be invoked

00:50:01.110 --> 00:50:03.940
to explain the origin of the
dark push or dark energy.

00:50:03.940 --> 00:50:07.610
So the idea is that all there is
is only a tiny fraction of what

00:50:07.610 --> 00:50:09.290
reality is actually made of.

00:50:09.290 --> 00:50:13.310
That our universe
itself, presumably

00:50:13.310 --> 00:50:16.485
of infinite spatial
extent, is but a tiny bit

00:50:16.485 --> 00:50:18.760
of a grander reality
called the multiverse which

00:50:18.760 --> 00:50:20.800
is depicted here by
these different bubbles.

00:50:20.800 --> 00:50:23.302
And these different bubbles
represent different corners

00:50:23.302 --> 00:50:24.760
of the multiverse,
each one of them

00:50:24.760 --> 00:50:26.180
with different laws of physics.

00:50:26.180 --> 00:50:29.610
And those laws of physics
varying across the multiverse

00:50:29.610 --> 00:50:31.670
that could explain why
our universe appears

00:50:31.670 --> 00:50:36.540
to be so strange with a dark
energy content that appears

00:50:36.540 --> 00:50:38.421
to be strangely
fine tuned for life

00:50:38.421 --> 00:50:39.920
to be able to exist
in our universe.

00:50:39.920 --> 00:50:42.390
And so this is what is called
the entropic principle,

00:50:42.390 --> 00:50:45.380
the idea that we live in a
corner of the multiverse that's

00:50:45.380 --> 00:50:48.200
good for life not because
our universe is strangely

00:50:48.200 --> 00:50:52.150
fine tuned, but because we
as biological life forms

00:50:52.150 --> 00:50:54.860
need for a long-leaved
cold universe

00:50:54.860 --> 00:50:59.000
with a stable rocky planet
going around a star.

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:00.710
We must be in a corner
of the multiverse

00:51:00.710 --> 00:51:02.950
where the fundamental
constants of nature

00:51:02.950 --> 00:51:06.720
are such that will allow this
kind of ecosystem to emerge.

00:51:06.720 --> 00:51:10.240
And so if we had a larger
reality like the multiverse

00:51:10.240 --> 00:51:14.510
with a large number of
possible universes to try life,

00:51:14.510 --> 00:51:16.820
we'd only be found in a corner
of the multiverse that's

00:51:16.820 --> 00:51:20.500
just right, and therefore that
would appear fine tuned to us.

00:51:20.500 --> 00:51:22.680
So here's the idea of the
multiverse, a collection

00:51:22.680 --> 00:51:25.110
of perhaps up to 10 to the
500 parallel universes, which

00:51:25.110 --> 00:51:28.232
is this spectacularly large
number of parallel universes,

00:51:28.232 --> 00:51:30.190
each one of them with
different laws of physics

00:51:30.190 --> 00:51:35.010
and different ways of mixing
the constants of nature.

00:51:35.010 --> 00:51:37.890
And we will be found in one
special place, a place where

00:51:37.890 --> 00:51:39.980
everything is just
right for us to exist.

00:51:41.020 --> 00:51:45.910
Not us as human beings, but
as examples of biological life

00:51:45.910 --> 00:51:47.980
forms that need very
special conditions.

00:51:47.980 --> 00:51:50.120
And so these are
all ideas that go on

00:51:50.120 --> 00:51:54.410
in the mind of our heroine,
the student woman that

00:51:54.410 --> 00:51:58.010
at the end of her night is
quite happy with the way

00:51:58.010 --> 00:51:59.380
her observations have gone.

00:52:00.628 --> 00:52:02.044
With the help of
big seer, she has

00:52:02.044 --> 00:52:04.320
looked as far away as
she possibly could.

00:52:04.320 --> 00:52:07.070
And she has gathered a lot
of data about dark matter

00:52:07.070 --> 00:52:11.450
that she hopes to be able
to decrypt and understand

00:52:11.450 --> 00:52:13.550
in order to crack this mystery.

00:52:13.550 --> 00:52:15.880
And so this is
how her night ends

00:52:15.880 --> 00:52:17.700
and this is how this talk ends.

00:52:20.200 --> 00:52:21.660
"She sits down.

00:52:21.660 --> 00:52:23.780
The big blue body of
water in front of her

00:52:23.780 --> 00:52:26.250
seems to go on without
edges and without end.

00:52:27.370 --> 00:52:29.600
She can feel the warm hand
of the sun on her face.

00:52:30.780 --> 00:52:32.160
She feels happy.

00:52:32.160 --> 00:52:33.770
The night's work has gone well.

00:52:33.770 --> 00:52:37.380
Big seer has done a great job,
the best that could be done.

00:52:37.380 --> 00:52:38.360
She can go home now.

00:52:39.490 --> 00:52:41.670
But her job has only just begun.

00:52:41.670 --> 00:52:44.290
There is much more left to do
in the coming weeks and months

00:52:44.290 --> 00:52:47.310
before she could make sense of
what big seer saw last night.

00:52:48.372 --> 00:52:49.580
She is looking forward to it.

00:52:50.620 --> 00:52:52.130
Letters, and words,
and entire books

00:52:52.130 --> 00:52:54.331
are hidden in what big
seer has given her, written

00:52:54.331 --> 00:52:56.080
in the strange tongue
of the all there is.

00:52:57.034 --> 00:52:58.575
Little by little,
she will understand

00:52:58.575 --> 00:53:00.390
it better and better.

00:53:00.390 --> 00:53:02.900
All she needs to do is
ask the right questions

00:53:02.900 --> 00:53:06.220
in the right way, and she
might learn the truth.

00:53:06.220 --> 00:53:09.820
She smiles and the sun
smiles back at her."

00:53:09.820 --> 00:53:11.876
So thank you very much
for having me here today.

00:53:11.876 --> 00:53:13.250
It's been a great
pleasure, and I

00:53:13.250 --> 00:53:14.791
am very happy to
take your questions.

00:53:14.791 --> 00:53:16.098
Thank you.

