for-- except perhaps

00:57:01.380 --> 00:57:04.850
for redshift or technical
words that you don't want

00:57:04.850 --> 00:57:07.270
to use because they are
jargony and that's fine.

00:57:07.270 --> 00:57:08.900
But 2,000 words
would be already too

00:57:08.900 --> 00:57:11.740
big a list to impose any
meaningful restrictions

00:57:11.740 --> 00:57:13.690
on your way of
expressing yourself.

00:57:13.690 --> 00:57:16.640
On other hand, 500
words would be too few.

00:57:16.640 --> 00:57:18.800
And you couldn't make
it work, I don't think,

00:57:18.800 --> 00:57:21.590
with 500 because it
becomes too hard.

00:57:21.590 --> 00:57:24.480
And it becomes really cumbersome
to say almost anything

00:57:24.480 --> 00:57:25.280
with only 500.

00:57:25.280 --> 00:57:28.410
So 1,000 words is actually
a nice sweet spot.

00:57:28.410 --> 00:57:33.140
And it hard enough,
but not impossible.

00:57:33.140 --> 00:57:36.340
And I think if you
tweak it to either side,

00:57:36.340 --> 00:57:39.030
you might find that it becomes
either too easy-- in which case

00:57:39.030 --> 00:57:42.180
you fall back to a standard
way of expressing almost

00:57:42.180 --> 00:57:44.490
those concepts-- or
too hard, in which case

00:57:44.490 --> 00:57:47.689
it becomes more of an exercise
in style, which this one is

00:57:47.689 --> 00:57:48.730
only to a certain extent.

00:57:48.730 --> 00:57:50.780
The purpose of this is not
to be an exercise in style.

00:57:50.780 --> 00:57:52.520
It's to really talk
about things in a way

00:57:52.520 --> 00:57:54.450
that people will understand.

00:57:54.450 --> 00:57:56.416
And this is my hope.

00:57:56.416 --> 00:57:59.040
And it's up to my readers to see
whether I've succeeded or not.

00:57:59.040 --> 00:58:01.790
And that's why I'm also very
keen to hear from people what

00:58:01.790 --> 00:58:03.870
they think, whether it
works for them or not.

00:58:03.870 --> 00:58:06.280
So that's very much an
experiment on my side.

00:58:06.280 --> 00:58:08.915
AUDIENCE: So [INAUDIBLE]
universe expanding.

00:58:08.915 --> 00:58:10.290
The part I wasn't
too clear about

00:58:10.290 --> 00:58:12.500
is whether-- I've
read in some places

00:58:12.500 --> 00:58:14.340
that the medium that
the universe is in

00:58:14.340 --> 00:58:17.640
could actually be expanding in
addition to the galaxies moving

00:58:17.640 --> 00:58:20.140
away from one another, which
means that it could move faster

00:58:20.140 --> 00:58:22.431
than the speed of light since
whatever it is sitting on

00:58:22.431 --> 00:58:24.690
is actually moving or
stretching at the same time.

00:58:24.690 --> 00:58:26.740
Can you explain a
bit more about that?

00:58:26.740 --> 00:58:28.610
ROBERTO TROTTA:
So there's a lots

00:58:28.610 --> 00:58:30.860
of confusion about this
barrier of the speed of light.

00:58:30.860 --> 00:58:35.650
Some people mistakenly think
that-- because as we know,

00:58:35.650 --> 00:58:37.822
the speed of light is the
ultimate speed limit--

00:58:37.822 --> 00:58:40.030
galaxies cannot move away
from each other faster than

00:58:40.030 --> 00:58:40.940
the speed of light.

00:58:40.940 --> 00:58:42.530
That is plain wrong.

00:58:42.530 --> 00:58:45.560
Galaxies do move faster
away from each other

00:58:45.560 --> 00:58:46.560
than the speed of light.

00:58:46.560 --> 00:58:47.601
And they do so routinely.

00:58:47.601 --> 00:58:50.040
In fact, there is a large
number of the galaxies

00:58:50.040 --> 00:58:52.810
that we saw on that slide
that are moving away

00:58:52.810 --> 00:58:55.547
from us at faster than the speed
of light and always have been.

00:58:55.547 --> 00:58:57.880
Now that's a tricky bit,
because we think, well actually

00:58:57.880 --> 00:58:59.320
if those galaxies are
moving away faster

00:58:59.320 --> 00:59:01.330
than the speed of light, how
is it that we can see them?

00:59:01.330 --> 00:59:03.730
How is it that light can catch
up with us in the first place?

00:59:03.730 --> 00:59:05.650
So that's something that's
slightly counter intuitive

00:59:05.650 --> 00:59:07.800
about it, and it cannot
be explained except with

00:59:07.800 --> 00:59:08.350
generativity.

00:59:08.350 --> 00:59:12.441
So analogies such as if you
go downstream and the stream

00:59:12.441 --> 00:59:16.310
is faster, then you can
swim upward, upstream, you

00:59:16.310 --> 00:59:19.340
will never catch up [INAUDIBLE].

00:59:19.340 --> 00:59:21.600
And those analogies do
not work in cosmology

00:59:21.600 --> 00:59:23.190
because of generativity.

00:59:23.190 --> 00:59:25.640
So galaxies do move away
faster than the speed of light.

00:59:25.640 --> 00:59:27.970
But the point is
that it's not them

00:59:27.970 --> 00:59:29.994
moving in space faster
than the speed of light.

00:59:29.994 --> 00:59:31.410
It's the space
between them that's

00:59:31.410 --> 00:59:33.520
expanding faster than
the speed of light.

00:59:33.520 --> 00:59:35.740
So that doesn't break the
speed of light barrier,

00:59:35.740 --> 00:59:37.156
because the speed
of light barrier

00:59:37.156 --> 00:59:39.770
is for objects inside
space time to have

00:59:39.770 --> 00:59:42.490
so-called peculiar velocities--
that's to say velocities

00:59:42.490 --> 00:59:45.412
inside space time moving
from one place to another.

00:59:45.412 --> 00:59:46.870
But because it's
space time itself,

00:59:46.870 --> 00:59:50.490
the pizza dough if you like
in the analogy is expanding.

00:59:50.490 --> 00:59:53.960
The recession speed,
the speed at which

00:59:53.960 --> 00:59:57.640
are bolted onto space time are
moving away from each other

00:59:57.640 --> 01:00:00.220
can be faster than
the speed of light.

01:00:00.220 --> 01:00:04.180
And so that is a misconception
the things cannot move farther

01:00:04.180 --> 01:00:05.500
away than the speed of light.

01:00:05.500 --> 01:00:07.402
They do, and we observe
them all the time.

